{"title_page": "Anita Odia", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Anita Odia\n| image        = \n| caption      = Anita in 2017\n| birth_name   = Anita Caroline Odia - Feb. 12, in\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[Ikeja]], [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|[[Model (person)|Model]]|[[Actress]]|[[film producer]]}}\n| years_active = 2012-present\n| known_for    = {{unbulleted list\n  |''[[Beauty of The Mind, (2015 film)|Beauty of The Mind]]''\n  |''[[The Silverspoon (2017 film)|The Silverspoon]]''\n  |''[[Dry Tears (2018 Nigerian film)|Dry Tears]]''\n    }}\n| awards       = [[Anita Odia#awards and recognition|See below]]\n| net_worth    =\n| website      = {{URL|akeyssproductions.com/}}\n| signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Anita Caroline Odia''' is a [[Nigerian]] [[actress]] and [[Film producer|producer]] born on the 12th of February, in Lagos - [[Nigeria]]. She is the Chief Executive Officer of A. Keyss Productions,<ref>http://www.findglocal.com/NG/Gwarinpa/1690889887802566/A.-Keyss-Productions</ref> a film production company in the Federal Capital Territory, [[Abuja]] which is into making high budget Movies, Skits and Web series for the Nigerian market, such as: Beauty of The Mind, The Silverspoon and Dry Tears.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnita Caroline Odia was Born on February 12 in Ikeja, Lagos - Nigeria and she is the first of five children by a Cameroonian mother and a Nigerian father. Although born in Lagos, Anita's earliest years, including her primary education were spent in Bamenda, a city in northwestern Cameroon, before she returned to Nigeria for her Secondary School Education in Lagos and Kano states. She earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) at the University of Calabar, situated in the Capital of Cross River state, a port city in southern Nigeria that shares a border with Cameroon.\n\n==Career==\n\nAnita picked up interest\nin acting while at the University which led her to take part in a film training workshop in Nigeria's the federal capital, Abuja, in 2010, organized by the New York Film Academy in a calculated move that launched her into her acting career with a Diploma in acting. Having, prior to that registered as a member of the Actors Guild of Nigeria, Abuja Chapter, she soon landed her first role in the movie, Real Wife in 2012 and by her second role in 2013 in the movie Ladies Affair, Anita's love and passion for acting and the movie industry was no longer in doubt. (When did she establish her production outfit, Akeyss?) Subsequently ( By 2014) through her \u2018A Keyss Productions\u2019, she produced her first movie; \u2018Beauty of The Mind\u2019 where she played the role of a Supporting Actress which earned 2 nominations at the International Film Festival in London(which year) as well as a nomination in 2018, for the Best Independent Film Supporting Actress in the Hollywood And African Prestigious Awards \u2013 HAPAwards, a United States of America awards which recognizes outstanding individuals whose lives have been marked by extraordinary personal and professional accomplishments.\nWith such astounding success of her first film, Anita's wade into the movie production industry, alongside acting became swifter and more sure footed as she featured in several other movies such as: From the Street, Stay with Me, Ekwueme and His Investment (in which she acted alongside the Popular Nkem Owoh and the multiple awards winning Daniel K. Daniel), Eno my Calabar Love (starring alongside Ini Edo), and Ojuko The War Lord (featured alongside Eniola Badmus and Queen Nwokoye). By 2015, under her production company, A Keyss Productions, she Co-Produced Fast Cash and then Silver Spoon and Dry Tears both of which were produced solely in 2017 and 2019 respectively.\n\n==Personal life==\nAnita Caroline Odia has...\n\n==Filmography==\n\nAnita Keyss, the Nollywood who isn't slowing down in the additions to both feathers in her cap of producing/directing and starring, in the short span of her romance in the movie industry has an admirable number of movies kitty n her such as:\n\n* The Butcher\n* Yahoo Plus\n* When LoveDIes \n* Ladies Affair\n* Dry Tears\n* Silver Spoon \n* Fast Cash \n* Beauty of The Mind\n* Real Wife\t\n* From the Street\n* Stay with Me\n* Ekwueme and His Investment \n* Eno my Calabar Love\n* Ojuko The War Lord\n\n==awards and recognition==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odia, Anita}}\n[[Category:Living people|Odia, Anita]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Anita Odia\n| image        = \n| caption      = Anita in 2017\n| birth_name   = Anita Caroline Odia - Feb. 12, in\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[Ikeja]], [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|[[Model]]|[[Actress]]|[[film producer]]}}\n| years_active = 2012-present\n| known_for    = {{unbulleted list\n  |''[[Beauty of The Mind, (2015 film)|Beauty of The Mind]]''\n  |''[[The Silverspoon (2017 film)|The Silverspoon]]''\n  |''[[Dry Tears (2018 Nigerian film)|Dry Tears]]''\n    }}\n| awards       = [[Anita Odia#awards and recognition|See below]]\n| net_worth    =\n| website      = {{URL|akeyssproductions.com/}}\n| signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Anita Caroline Odia''' is a [[Nigerian]] [[actress]] and [[producer]] born on the 12th of February, in Lagos - [[Nigeria]]. She is the Chief Executive Officer of A. Keyss Productions,<ref>http://www.findglocal.com/NG/Gwarinpa/1690889887802566/A.-Keyss-Productions</ref> a film production company in the Federal Capital Territory, [[Abuja]] which is into making high budget Movies, Skits and Web series for the Nigerian market, such as: Beauty of The Mind, The Silverspoon and Dry Tears.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnita Caroline Odia was Born on February 12 in Ikeja, Lagos - Nigeria and she is the first of five children by a Cameroonian mother and a Nigerian father. Although born in Lagos, Anita's earliest years, including her primary education were spent in Bamenda, a city in northwestern Cameroon, before she returned to Nigeria for her Secondary School Education in Lagos and Kano states. She earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) at the University of Calabar, situated in the Capital of Cross River state, a port city in southern Nigeria that shares a border with Cameroon.\n\n==Career==\n\nAnita picked up interest\nin acting while at the University which led her to take part in a film training workshop in Nigeria's the federal capital, Abuja, in 2010, organized by the New York Film Academy in a calculated move that launched her into her acting career with a Diploma in acting. Having, prior to that registered as a member of the Actors Guild of Nigeria, Abuja Chapter, she soon landed her first role in the movie, Real Wife in 2012 and by her second role in 2013 in the movie Ladies Affair, Anita's love and passion for acting and the movie industry was no longer in doubt. (When did she establish her production outfit, Akeyss?) Subsequently ( By 2014) through her \u2018A Keyss Productions\u2019, she produced her first movie; \u2018Beauty of The Mind\u2019 where she played the role of a Supporting Actress which earned 2 nominations at the International Film Festival in London(which year) as well as a nomination in 2018, for the Best Independent Film Supporting Actress in the Hollywood And African Prestigious Awards \u2013 HAPAwards, a United States of America awards which recognizes outstanding individuals whose lives have been marked by extraordinary personal and professional accomplishments.\nWith such astounding success of her first film, Anita's wade into the movie production industry, alongside acting became swifter and more sure footed as she featured in several other movies such as: From the Street, Stay with Me, Ekwueme and His Investment (in which she acted alongside the Popular Nkem Owoh and the multiple awards winning Daniel K. Daniel), Eno my Calabar Love (starring alongside Ini Edo), and Ojuko The War Lord (featured alongside Eniola Badmus and Queen Nwokoye). By 2015, under her production company, A Keyss Productions, she Co-Produced Fast Cash and then Silver Spoon and Dry Tears both of which were produced solely in 2017 and 2019 respectively.\n\n==Personal life==\nAnita Caroline Odia has...\n\n==Filmography==\n\nAnita Keyss, the Nollywood who isn't slowing down in the additions to both feathers in her cap of producing/directing and starring, in the short span of her romance in the movie industry has an admirable number of movies kitty n her such as:\n\n* The Butcher\n* Yahoo Plus\n* When LoveDIes \n* Ladies Affair\n* Dry Tears\n* Silver Spoon \n* Fast Cash \n* Beauty of The Mind\n* Real Wife\t\n* From the Street\n* Stay with Me\n* Ekwueme and His Investment \n* Eno my Calabar Love\n* Ojuko The War Lord\n\n==awards and recognition==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odia, Anita}}\n[[Category:Living people|Odia, Anita]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Model\u2192Model (person),producer\u2192Film producer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anita_Odia"}
{"title_page": "Blackbear (musician)", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer, rapper, songwriter, and record producer from Florida}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Blackbear\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Matthew Tyler Musto (musician-songwriter).jpg\n| caption          = Musto in 2008\n| birth_name       = Matthew Tyler Musto\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1990|11|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Pittston, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Palm Coast]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[Trap music|trap]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[indie pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|Alamo|Beartrap<ref>https://open.spotify.com/artist/2cFrymmkijnjDg9SS92EPM?si=rL-eoAGiR8qMo_EyBFSH9Q</ref>\n|[[Island Records|Island]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mansionz]]\n*[[Andrew Goldstein (musician)|Andrew Goldstein]]\n*[[Mike Shinoda]]\n*[[Mod Sun]]\n*[[Ne-Yo]]\n*[[Riff Raff (rapper)|Riff Raff]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|beartrap.la}}\n}}\n'''Matthew Tyler Musto''' (born November 27, 1990), known professionally as '''Blackbear''' (stylized as '''blackbear'''), is an American musician, singer, songwriter, and record producer.<ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6078323/blackbear/biography|title=blackbear \u2013 Biography \u2013 Billboard|publisher=}}</ref> He has released five studio albums, six EPs, one mixtape and two collaborative albums. Musto is also a member of the alternative hip hop/R&B duo [[Mansionz]] with American singer and rapper [[Mike Posner]].\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132014: Early career===\nIn high school, Musto was the singer of Florida-based garage band Polaroid. They released one album, ''Paint The Town'', one EP, ''Inside And Out'', and one demo, ''The Cure Demo''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Polaroid on PureVolume|url=http://www.purevolume.com/polaroidd|website=PureVolume|accessdate=5 December 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114193740/http://www.purevolume.com/polaroidd|archive-date=14 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> They were signed to Leakmob Records.<ref name=\"reverbnation.com\">{{cite web|title=Mat Musto {{!}} Rock from Atlanta, GA|url=https://www.reverbnation.com/matmusto|website=ReverbNation|accessdate=6 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> Musto dropped out of school in the 9th grade to focus on music.<ref name=\"complex\">{{cite web |title=Rapper and R&B Singer Blackbear is Reinvention, Personified |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/04/rapper-and-r-and-b-singer-blackbear-is-reinvention-personified |website=Complex |accessdate=3 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Polaroid, Musto began a solo career when he moved to Atlanta to work with [[Ne-Yo]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/interviews/2017/11/blackbear-interview|title=The Pop Star Who Never Wanted to be Famous|last=Caitlin|website=Pigeons & Planes}}</ref> He put out his first EP entitled ''Brightness'' in 2008, followed by ''Contrast'' in 2009, and ''Exposure'' in 2010. He put out a Christmas song with [[Tyler Carter]], then-member of the band [[Woe, Is Me]] in 2010, shortly followed by a new single, 'Douche Bag'. In July 2011, Musto released his ''Year of the Blackbear'' EP. In fall 2011, he decided to take his nickname of Blackbear and use it as his pseudonym for making music. The first song to be released with the Blackbear moniker was Mike Posner's song, 'Marauder Music' in November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Internet Archive Search: creator%3A%22Matthew Tyler Musto%22|url=https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Matthew+Tyler+Musto%22|website=archive.org|accessdate=6 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMusto co-wrote Justin Bieber's \"[[Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)|Boyfriend]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/211223/justin-bieber-releases-new-single-boyfriend-audio/|title=Justin Bieber Releases New Single, 'Boyfriend' [Audio]|publisher=}}</ref> a number two hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in early 2012. Intent on pursuing a career as an R&B singer, Musto released his debut EP ''Foreplay'' on April 20, 2012, and his debut mixtape ''Sex'' on October 31, 2012. Both releases were under the name Blackbear, and ''Sex'' featured collaborations from fellow \"Boyfriend\" co-writer Mike Posner, along with producers, singers, and songwriters James Blake and Maejor Ali.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rubenstein|first1=Jenna|title=blackbear's 'Sex the Mixtape' features blackbear's \u2018Sex The Mixtape\u2019 Features Collabs with Mike Posner, T. Mills, and Other Really Famous People|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2302551/blackbear-sex-the-mixtape/|website=MTV|publisher=MTV|date=November 1, 2012|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> He also appeared on [[MGK]]'s End of the Road from the ''[[Lace Up]]'' album. Blackbear released an EP, ''The Afterglow'', on April 20, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-afterglow-ep/id867630879|title=The Afterglow \u2013 EP by Blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=April 20, 2014|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> This landed him as number four on Billboard's Uncharted listing of releases from upcoming artists.<ref name=\"billboard.com\" />\n\nIn 2014, Blackbear became one of the first independent artists to monetize streaming on [[SoundCloud]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6228878/soundcloud-monetization-advertising|title=SoundCloud Debuts Monetization Play With 'On SoundCloud', Announces $100 Million In Funding|publipopisinthenightsher=}}</ref>\n\n===2015: ''Deadroses'' and ''Help''===\nBlackbear released his first full-length album, ''Deadroses'', a self-released set of 10 tracks, on February 14, 2015. The album received favorable reviews, one of which stating that the album had \"pleasantly mixed together a plethora of genres, sounds, and emotions to create a completely cohesive and unique project.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rlgtcanada.com/2015/07/29/did-blackbear-discretely-drop-the-album-of-the-year/|title=Did Blackbear Discretely Drop The Album Of The Year?|date=29 July 2015|website=rlgtcanada.com}}</ref> The lead single, \"Idfc\", charted on ''Billboard'''s R&B Hot 100 and held a spot on the ''Billboard'' R&B charts for over a year. The track has earned millions of streams on both SoundCloud and [[Spotify]]. It has been streamed over 22.5 million times on SoundCloud and Idfc (Tarro Remix) has over 192 million views as of June 2019. \"Idfc\" shot Blackbear to the top 20 of the [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6078323/blackbear/chart?f=1230&sort=position|title=Blackbear - Chart history - Billboard|website=www.billboard.com}}</ref> The second single, \"90210\", features G-Eazy and gained over 11 million streams on SoundCloud and over 9 million streams on Spotify.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hamilton|first1=BreeAngela|title=Review: Deadroses by blackbear|url=http://coogradio.com/2015/02/review-deadroses-by-blackbear/|website=coogradio|publisher=Coogradio|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"spotify.com\">{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/2cFrymmkijnjDg9SS92EPM|title=blackbear|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, his track \"NYLA\" was featured in the documentary [[Hot Girls Wanted]] on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4382552/|title=Hot Girls Wanted|date=29 May 2015|publisher=|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n''Deadroses'' was followed by the EP ''Dead'', which featured acoustic versions of four ''Deadroses'' tracks, as well as one new track, \"Weak When Ur Around\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dead-acoustic-ep/id991111726|title=Dead (Acoustic) \u2013 EP by blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=June 2, 2015|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dead-acoustic-ep/id991111726/|title=Dead (Acoustic) \u2013 EP by blackbear on Apple Music|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe released his second full-length album, ''Help'', on November 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/help/id1083607683|title=Help by blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=November 27, 2015|access-date=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016: ''Drink Bleach'', ''Cashmere Noose'', and Mansionz ===\nOn April 20, 2016, Blackbear released his fourth EP, ''Drink Bleach'', which featured appearances from \"[[Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)|Boyfriend]]\" collaborator Mike Posner as well as American hip-hop recording artist and [[The HBK Gang]] co-founder [[P-Lo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/drink-bleach-ep/id1124677370|title=Drink Bleach \u2013 EP by blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=April 20, 2016|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the year, Blackbear collaborated with other artists such as American rock band Linkin Park as well as Jacob Sartorius and [[Phoebe Ryan]], and he toured with Hoodie Allen, whose 2016 track and ''[[Happy Camper]]'' promotional single \"Champagne and Pools\" also featured Blackbear. Mid-year, he joined [[Kyle (musician)|Super Duper Kyle]] and [[Tinashe]] on their tours.\n\nOn August 2, 2016, Blackbear released his fifth EP, titled ''Cashmere Noose'', through SoundCloud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/iamblackbear/sets/cashmere-noose|title=cashmere noose|publisher=}}</ref> He handled the EP's production entirely on his own through his production collective Bear Trap Records. The EP originally included a feature from American rapper Mod Sun on the track \"Spent All My Money On Rick Owens Cargo Pants\", but this track was removed from the EP's final cut and replaced with \"Wanderlust\" and \"Flirt Right Back\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Blackbear (Ft. MOD SUN) \u2013 Spent All My Money On Rick Owens Cargo Pants|url=https://genius.com/Blackbear-spent-all-my-money-on-rick-owens-cargo-pants-lyrics|language=en|accessdate=2017-04-08}}</ref> The original version of ''Cashmere Noose'', however, can still be found on Blackbear's SoundCloud page.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/iamblackbear/sets/cashmere-noose|title=cashmere noose|website=SoundCloud|language=en|access-date=2017-04-08}}</ref> The final version of ''Cashmere Noose'' peaked at number one on the iTunes R&B charts and number six overall on iTunes, just behind [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonce's]] ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'' and [[Drake (musician)|Drake's]] ''[[Views (album)|Views]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopweeklyradio.com/chart-toppers-112216/|title=[CHART TOPPERS] This Week in Music Sales: Nov. 22, 2016 \u2013 Hip Hop Weekly Radio|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBlackbear was also featured in [[Olivia O'Brien]]'s single \"Root Beer Float\", released September 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kress|first1=Bryan|title=Olivia O'Brien Releases Sugary 'Root Beer Float,' Feat. blackbear: Exclusive Premiere|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7511035/olivia-obrien-root-beer-float-blackbear-premiere|website=Billboard|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> He also released the track \"If I Could I Would Feel Nothing,\" a freestyle originally posted on his Twitter that eventually became a promotional single for his upcoming third studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/iamblackbear/status/804845291824447488?lang=en|title=blackbear on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2016, Blackbear formed the alternative hip hop and R&B duo Mansionz with frequent collaborator and singer-songwriter Mike Posner. Mansionz have been active since 2016 and are based out of Los Angeles, California. The duo released their debut single, \"STFU\", on December 9, 2016. The song features rapper [[Spark Master Tape]]. Mansionz released two more singles in early 2017, \"Rich White Girls\" and \"Dennis Rodman\", the latter of which features the basketball player [[Dennis Rodman]]. Both of these singles, along with \"STFU\", were featured on Mansionz' [[Mansionz (album)|self-titled debut album]] which was released on March 24, 2017, and features guest appearances from G-Eazy, [[Soren Bryce]], [[Cyhi the Prynce|CyHi the Prynce]], and Snoozegod.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coleman III|first1=C. Vernon|title=G-Eazy and CyHi The Prynce Show Up on Mansionz\u2019s New Album - XXL|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/03/g-eazy-cyhi-the-prynce-mansionzs-new-album/|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Digital Druglord'' and ''Cybersex''===\nOn January 29, 2017, he posted the track \"Make Daddy Proud\", which was a remix of Jeremy Zucker's \"Heavy\", on his SoundCloud page. The track was later confirmed to be the next promotional single for his third studio album ''[[Digital Druglord]]''. On March 17, 2017, Blackbear released the lead single for the album, titled \"Do Re Mi\".<ref name=\"do re mi\">{{Citation|title=blackbear \u2013 do re mi|url=https://genius.com/Blackbear-do-re-mi-lyrics|language=en|accessdate=2017-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2017, shortly before the release of ''Digital Druglord'', Blackbear released a short acoustic EP titled ''Salt'' on his SoundCloud. ''Digital Druglord'' was released on April 20, 2017, featuring the single \"Do Re Mi\" along with promotional singles \"If I Could I Would Feel Nothing\" and \"Make Daddy Proud\".<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/digital-druglord/id1216872048</ref> In an interview with Vice's music channel [[Vice (magazine)|Noisey]], he revealed that he wrote ''Digital Druglord'' while in the hospital based on his experiences with alcohol and drugs. He states that the cover art for the album, a woman with pill bottles attached to her chest, is not to glorify the use of pharmaceuticals, but because he now has to take prescription drugs to stay alive due to his illness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/pa3wvz/blackbear-interview-cybersex-2017|title=blackbear Is Extremely Famous, Even If You Don't Know Who He Is|date=2017-11-14|work=Noisey|access-date=2018-06-24|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2017, he signed a 10 million dollar distribution deal with [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] that gave the label the rights to ''Digital Druglord'' and the following studio album and their respective singles.<ref name=\"complex\" />\n\nOn August 18, 2017, Blackbear announced his next project, a mixtape named ''[[Cybersex (album)|Cybersex]]''. The name ''Cybersex'' comes from Blackbear's infatuation with the internet. In an interview with [[Pigeons & Planes]], he talks about how the internet is why he is here and how cybersex was the first form of sexting. He states how he finds the internet interesting and how you can now fall asleep with your loved one in another country, due to technology.<ref name=\":0\" /> He released a song on SoundCloud in September 2017 titled \"froze over\". The track was written and produced by Good Intent and Blackbear and it would later appear in ''Cybersex'' as a two part interlude titled \"thursday/froze over\". On October 6, 2017, a song titled \"Playboy Shit\", which features rapper Lil Aaron, was released on Blackbear's [[Pornhub|PornHub]] account and confirmed to be a part of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/playboy-s-t-feat-lil-aaron-single/id1293942675|title=Playboy S**t (feat. lil aaron) - Single by blackbear on Apple Music|website=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=2017-10-14}}</ref> On October 20, 2017, Blackbear released the single \"Bright Pink Tims\" featuring [[Cam'ron]]. This day also marked the first day of his tour in support of Fall Out Boy's [[The Mania Tour|Mania Tour]], running until November 18. On November 27, 2017, Musto's 27th birthday, ''Cybersex'' was released.\n\nOn April 26, 2018, \"About You\", a song written by Linkin Park's [[Mike Shinoda]] regarding the death of his bandmate [[Chester Bennington]], was released featuring Blackbear.<ref>{{cite web|title=LINKIN PARK's MIKE SHINODA: 'I Had Terrible Days, And Now I Have Less Bad Days'|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/linkin-parks-mike-shinoda-i-had-terrible-days-and-now-i-have-less-bad-days/|website=BLABBERMOUTH.NET|accessdate=12 May 2018|date=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2018, Blackbear released his single titled \"the 1\", produced by FRND.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blackbear Is Back With \"The 1\" |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/blackbear-is-back-with-the-1-new-song.1980033.html |website=HotNewHipHop |accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019: ''Anonymous'' and ''Sad But Chillin''===\n\nIn February 2019, Blackbear said he would be releasing a single per week until April 26, which is when his fourth studio album would be released. On Valentine's Day 2019, he released his single \"1 SIDED LOVE\". On February 20, he released his single \"HIGH1X\". On March 13, he released his single \"SWEAR TO GOD\" during [[Zane Lowe]]'s transmission on [[Beats 1]].\n\nApril 26, 2019, he released the full album, ''[[Anonymous (Blackbear album)|Anonymous]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inkedmag.com/original-news/exclusive-blackbear-dishes-on-his-upcoming-album|title=Exclusive: Blackbear Dishes on His Upcoming Album|last=Preston|first=Devon|website=Tattoo Ideas, Artists and Models|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|title=ANONYMOUS by blackbear|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/anonymous/1453250142|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> This album is his longest album yet, containing 18 tracks lasting a total of 51 minutes. Along with the release of this album, he posted a photo on Instagram with a caption discussing his gratefulness of a second chance after his health complications at age 27, and he discusses how meaningful this album is to him. \n\nOn August 23, 2019, he released the lead single \"[[Hot Girl Bummer]]\" from his upcoming fifth studio album \"Sad But Chillin\".<ref>https://www.altpress.com/news/blackblack-hot-girl-bummer-video/</ref>\nOn November 13, 2019, Blackbear released the one off single \"[[Tongue Tied (Marshmello, Yungblud and Blackbear song)|Tongue Tied]]\", with American producer [[Marshmello]] and English singer [[Yungblud]].\nOn January 16, 2020, he released second single \"Me & Ur Ghost\".\n\n== Producing and songwriting ==\nIn addition to his own music, Musto has produced and written for many popular artists. He has collaborated with numerous musical artists such as [[Marc E. Bassy]], [[Justin Bieber]], [[G-Eazy]], [[Mike Posner]], [[Maejor Ali]], [[Palisades (band)|Palisades]], [[Machine Gun Kelly (rapper)|Machine Gun Kelly]], [[Rick Ross]], [[Cam\u2019ron]], [[2 Chainz]], [[Mod Sun]], [[Rivers Cuomo]], [[Childish Gambino]], [[Billie Eilish]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Mike Shinoda]], Tiny Meat Gang, and [[Jacob Sartorius]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pop-buzz.com/just-music/who-is-blackbear/|title=Who Is blackbear And Why Do Your Faves Love Him?|website=Pop Buzz}}</ref>\nHe co-wrote \"[[Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)|Boyfriend]]\" by Justin Bieber, alongside Mike Posner, which debuted at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Justin Bieber's 'Boyfriend' Debuts at No. 2 on Hot 100|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/497102/justin-biebers-boyfriend-debuts-at-no-2-on-hot-100|website=Billboard|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.warnerchappell.com/song-details/WW%20010026937%2000/2bcabefc-9461-4f97-9294-160347dafb3d|website=www.warnerchappell.com|access-date=2019-03-06|title=Boyfriend - Warner/Chappell Music}}</ref> He also produced the title track from G-Eazy's album These Things Happen, as well as featuring on the album.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Producing and Songwriting Credits\n!TITLE\n!ARTIST\n!YEAR\n!ROLE\n|-\n|\"End of the Road\"\n|[[Machine Gun Kelly (musician)|Machine Gun Kelly]]\n|2012\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Boyfriend\"\n|[[Justin Bieber]]\n|2012\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|\"These Things Happen\"\n|[[G-Eazy]]\n|2014\n|Songwriter/producer<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Look Up\"\n|[[Mod Sun]]\n|2015\n|Producer<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Mind Games\"\n|[[Palisades (band)|Palisades]]\n|2015\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Sorry For Now\"\n|[[Linkin Park]]\n|2017\n|Producer<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|\"talk is overrated\"\n|[[Jeremy Zucker]]\n|2017\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"About You\"\n|[[Mike Shinoda]]\n|2018\n|Songwriter/producer<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nMusto was born in [[Pittston, Pennsylvania]]and is the love child of EMINEM and JUSTIN BIEBER and moved to [[Daytona Beach, Florida]] as a child.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Deiter|first1=Olivia|title=Blackbear|url=https://shsthetorch.com/22355/showcase/blackbear/|website=the Torch|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"complex\"/> Musto was raised in [[Palm Coast, Florida]].<ref name=\"reverbnation.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/pa3wvz/blackbear-interview-cybersex-2017|title=blackbear Is Extremely Famous, Even If You Don't Know Who He Is|date=2017-11-14|work=Noisey|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-us}}</ref> He moved to [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] and then [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] in his late teens.\n\nIn April 2016, he was hospitalized and diagnosed with chronic pancreatitis due to excessive alcohol use. During his time in the hospital, he wrote his album \"Digital Druglord\" and took this time to become sober.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blackbear Looked Death in The Eyes And Released His Best Album to Date |url=https://www.hypefresh.co/blackbear-looked-death-in-the-eyes-and-released-his-best-album-to-date/ |website=Hypefresh Inc |accessdate=23 January 2020 |date=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=How a Near-Death Experience Helped blackbear Make His Most Successful Album Yet |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7785135/blackbear-digital-druglord-album-interview |website=Billboard |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref> In November 2018, Musto collaborated with the brand [[PopSockets]] and donated 50% of the proceeds of his branded products to Mission: Cure, a non-profit dedicated to finding a cure for chronic pancreatitis.<ref>{{cite web |title=im 1 of many w/ chronic pancreatitis mission : cure are closer everyday to finding a cure. donating half to them!http://popsockets.com/pages/blackbear\u00a0pic.twitter.com/2wT20pp5Dn |url=https://twitter.com/iamblackbear/status/1063566734815195136?lang=en |website=Twitter |accessdate=23 January 2020 |language=en |date=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2019, Musto announced that he and his girlfriend Michele Maturo were expecting their first child in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shoemaker |first1=Whitney |title=blackbear and Michele Maturo announce pregnancy |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/blackbear-michele-maturo-pregnancy-baby-boy/ |website=Alternative Press |accessdate=4 October 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref> On January 29, 2020, the couple announced the birth of their son, Midnight Thomas Musto, born on January 26, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=blackbear on Instagram: \u201cMIDNIGHT THOMAS MUSTO IS HERE im a papa im a daddy!!!!!!!! omg omg i havent stopp crying\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B76uG3unKVS/ |website=Instagram |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Michele on Instagram: \u201cMidnight Thomas Musto is here + healthy & weighs 7lb 3oz & arrived January 26th. No other way to describe how I feel besides perfect.\u2026\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B76l_XYnA54/ |website=Instagram |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Blackbear discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''Deadroses'' (2015)\n* ''Help'' (2015)\n* ''[[Digital Druglord]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Anonymous (Blackbear album)|Anonymous]]'' (2019)\n* ''Sad But Chillin''<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8ZiK0CHY0n/|title=changed name of album to sad but chillin|accessdate=March 4, 2020|via=[[Instagram]]}}</ref> (2020)\n'''Collaborative albums'''\n* ''Hotel Motel'' {{small|(with [[Mod Sun]])}} (2016)\n* ''[[Mansionz]]'' {{small|(with [[Mike Posner]])}} (2017)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{Blackbear}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American indie pop musicians]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pop rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Florida]]\n[[Catgeory:Singers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Trap musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer, rapper, songwriter, and record producer from Florida}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Blackbear\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Matthew Tyler Musto (musician-songwriter).jpg\n| caption          = Musto in 2008\n| birth_name       = Matthew Tyler Musto\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1990|11|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Pittston, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Palm Coast]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[Trap music|trap]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[indie pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|Alamo|Beartrap<ref>https://open.spotify.com/artist/2cFrymmkijnjDg9SS92EPM?si=rL-eoAGiR8qMo_EyBFSH9Q</ref>\n|[[Island Records|Island]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mansionz]]\n*[[Andrew Goldstein (musician)|Andrew Goldstein]]\n*[[Mike Shinoda]]\n*[[Mod Sun]]\n*[[Ne-Yo]]\n*[[Riff Raff (rapper)|Riff Raff]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|beartrap.la}}\n}}\n'''Matthew Tyler Musto''' (born November 27, 1990), known professionally as '''Blackbear''' (stylized as '''blackbear'''), is an American musician, singer, songwriter, and record producer.<ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6078323/blackbear/biography|title=blackbear \u2013 Biography \u2013 Billboard|publisher=}}</ref> He has released five studio albums, six EPs, one mixtape and two collaborative albums. Musto is also a member of the alternative hip hop/R&B duo [[Mansionz]] with American singer and rapper [[Mike Posner]].\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132014: Early career===\nIn high school, Musto was the singer of Florida-based garage band Polaroid. They released one album, ''Paint The Town'', one EP, ''Inside And Out'', and one demo, ''The Cure Demo''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Polaroid on PureVolume|url=http://www.purevolume.com/polaroidd|website=PureVolume|accessdate=5 December 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114193740/http://www.purevolume.com/polaroidd|archive-date=14 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> They were signed to Leakmob Records.<ref name=\"reverbnation.com\">{{cite web|title=Mat Musto {{!}} Rock from Atlanta, GA|url=https://www.reverbnation.com/matmusto|website=ReverbNation|accessdate=6 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> Musto dropped out of school in the 9th grade to focus on music.<ref name=\"complex\">{{cite web |title=Rapper and R&B Singer Blackbear is Reinvention, Personified |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/04/rapper-and-r-and-b-singer-blackbear-is-reinvention-personified |website=Complex |accessdate=3 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Polaroid, Musto began a solo career when he moved to Atlanta to work with [[Ne-Yo]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/interviews/2017/11/blackbear-interview|title=The Pop Star Who Never Wanted to be Famous|last=Caitlin|website=Pigeons & Planes}}</ref> He put out his first EP entitled ''Brightness'' in 2008, followed by ''Contrast'' in 2009, and ''Exposure'' in 2010. He put out a Christmas song with [[Tyler Carter]], then-member of the band [[Woe, Is Me]] in 2010, shortly followed by a new single, 'Douche Bag'. In July 2011, Musto released his ''Year of the Blackbear'' EP. In fall 2011, he decided to take his nickname of Blackbear and use it as his pseudonym for making music. The first song to be released with the Blackbear moniker was Mike Posner's song, 'Marauder Music' in November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Internet Archive Search: creator%3A%22Matthew Tyler Musto%22|url=https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Matthew+Tyler+Musto%22|website=archive.org|accessdate=6 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMusto co-wrote Justin Bieber's \"[[Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)|Boyfriend]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/211223/justin-bieber-releases-new-single-boyfriend-audio/|title=Justin Bieber Releases New Single, 'Boyfriend' [Audio]|publisher=}}</ref> a number two hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in early 2012. Intent on pursuing a career as an R&B singer, Musto released his debut EP ''Foreplay'' on April 20, 2012, and his debut mixtape ''Sex'' on October 31, 2012. Both releases were under the name Blackbear, and ''Sex'' featured collaborations from fellow \"Boyfriend\" co-writer Mike Posner, along with producers, singers, and songwriters James Blake and Maejor Ali.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rubenstein|first1=Jenna|title=blackbear's 'Sex the Mixtape' features blackbear's \u2018Sex The Mixtape\u2019 Features Collabs with Mike Posner, T. Mills, and Other Really Famous People|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2302551/blackbear-sex-the-mixtape/|website=MTV|publisher=MTV|date=November 1, 2012|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> He also appeared on [[MGK]]'s End of the Road from the ''[[Lace Up]]'' album. Blackbear released an EP, ''The Afterglow'', on April 20, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-afterglow-ep/id867630879|title=The Afterglow \u2013 EP by Blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=April 20, 2014|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> This landed him as number four on Billboard's Uncharted listing of releases from upcoming artists.<ref name=\"billboard.com\" />\n\nIn 2014, Blackbear became one of the first independent artists to monetize streaming on [[SoundCloud]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6228878/soundcloud-monetization-advertising|title=SoundCloud Debuts Monetization Play With 'On SoundCloud', Announces $100 Million In Funding|publipopisinthenightsher=}}</ref>\n\n===2015: ''Deadroses'' and ''Help''===\nBlackbear released his first full-length album, ''Deadroses'', a self-released set of 10 tracks, on February 14, 2015. The album received favorable reviews, one of which stating that the album had \"pleasantly mixed together a plethora of genres, sounds, and emotions to create a completely cohesive and unique project.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rlgtcanada.com/2015/07/29/did-blackbear-discretely-drop-the-album-of-the-year/|title=Did Blackbear Discretely Drop The Album Of The Year?|date=29 July 2015|website=rlgtcanada.com}}</ref> The lead single, \"Idfc\", charted on ''Billboard'''s R&B Hot 100 and held a spot on the ''Billboard'' R&B charts for over a year. The track has earned millions of streams on both SoundCloud and [[Spotify]]. It has been streamed over 22.5 million times on SoundCloud and Idfc (Tarro Remix) has over 192 million views as of June 2019. \"Idfc\" shot Blackbear to the top 20 of the [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6078323/blackbear/chart?f=1230&sort=position|title=Blackbear - Chart history - Billboard|website=www.billboard.com}}</ref> The second single, \"90210\", features G-Eazy and gained over 11 million streams on SoundCloud and over 9 million streams on Spotify.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hamilton|first1=BreeAngela|title=Review: Deadroses by blackbear|url=http://coogradio.com/2015/02/review-deadroses-by-blackbear/|website=coogradio|publisher=Coogradio|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"spotify.com\">{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/2cFrymmkijnjDg9SS92EPM|title=blackbear|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, his track \"NYLA\" was featured in the documentary [[Hot Girls Wanted]] on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4382552/|title=Hot Girls Wanted|date=29 May 2015|publisher=|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n''Deadroses'' was followed by the EP ''Dead'', which featured acoustic versions of four ''Deadroses'' tracks, as well as one new track, \"Weak When Ur Around\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dead-acoustic-ep/id991111726|title=Dead (Acoustic) \u2013 EP by blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=June 2, 2015|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dead-acoustic-ep/id991111726/|title=Dead (Acoustic) \u2013 EP by blackbear on Apple Music|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe released his second full-length album, ''Help'', on November 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/help/id1083607683|title=Help by blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=November 27, 2015|access-date=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016: ''Drink Bleach'', ''Cashmere Noose'', and Mansionz ===\nOn April 20, 2016, Blackbear released his fourth EP, ''Drink Bleach'', which featured appearances from \"[[Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)|Boyfriend]]\" collaborator Mike Posner as well as American hip-hop recording artist and [[The HBK Gang]] co-founder [[P-Lo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/drink-bleach-ep/id1124677370|title=Drink Bleach \u2013 EP by blackbear on iTunes|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=April 20, 2016|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the year, Blackbear collaborated with other artists such as American rock band Linkin Park as well as Jacob Sartorius and [[Phoebe Ryan]], and he toured with Hoodie Allen, whose 2016 track and ''[[Happy Camper]]'' promotional single \"Champagne and Pools\" also featured Blackbear. Mid-year, he joined [[Kyle (musician)|Super Duper Kyle]] and [[Tinashe]] on their tours.\n\nOn August 2, 2016, Blackbear released his fifth EP, titled ''Cashmere Noose'', through SoundCloud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/iamblackbear/sets/cashmere-noose|title=cashmere noose|publisher=}}</ref> He handled the EP's production entirely on his own through his production collective Bear Trap Records. The EP originally included a feature from American rapper Mod Sun on the track \"Spent All My Money On Rick Owens Cargo Pants\", but this track was removed from the EP's final cut and replaced with \"Wanderlust\" and \"Flirt Right Back\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Blackbear (Ft. MOD SUN) \u2013 Spent All My Money On Rick Owens Cargo Pants|url=https://genius.com/Blackbear-spent-all-my-money-on-rick-owens-cargo-pants-lyrics|language=en|accessdate=2017-04-08}}</ref> The original version of ''Cashmere Noose'', however, can still be found on Blackbear's SoundCloud page.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/iamblackbear/sets/cashmere-noose|title=cashmere noose|website=SoundCloud|language=en|access-date=2017-04-08}}</ref> The final version of ''Cashmere Noose'' peaked at number one on the iTunes R&B charts and number six overall on iTunes, just behind [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonce's]] ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'' and [[Drake (musician)|Drake's]] ''[[Views (album)|Views]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopweeklyradio.com/chart-toppers-112216/|title=[CHART TOPPERS] This Week in Music Sales: Nov. 22, 2016 \u2013 Hip Hop Weekly Radio|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBlackbear was also featured in [[Olivia O'Brien]]'s single \"Root Beer Float\", released September 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kress|first1=Bryan|title=Olivia O'Brien Releases Sugary 'Root Beer Float,' Feat. blackbear: Exclusive Premiere|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7511035/olivia-obrien-root-beer-float-blackbear-premiere|website=Billboard|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> He also released the track \"If I Could I Would Feel Nothing,\" a freestyle originally posted on his Twitter that eventually became a promotional single for his upcoming third studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/iamblackbear/status/804845291824447488?lang=en|title=blackbear on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2016, Blackbear formed the alternative hip hop and R&B duo Mansionz with frequent collaborator and singer-songwriter Mike Posner. Mansionz have been active since 2016 and are based out of Los Angeles, California. The duo released their debut single, \"STFU\", on December 9, 2016. The song features rapper [[Spark Master Tape]]. Mansionz released two more singles in early 2017, \"Rich White Girls\" and \"Dennis Rodman\", the latter of which features the basketball player [[Dennis Rodman]]. Both of these singles, along with \"STFU\", were featured on Mansionz' [[Mansionz (album)|self-titled debut album]] which was released on March 24, 2017, and features guest appearances from G-Eazy, [[Soren Bryce]], [[Cyhi the Prynce|CyHi the Prynce]], and Snoozegod.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coleman III|first1=C. Vernon|title=G-Eazy and CyHi The Prynce Show Up on Mansionz\u2019s New Album - XXL|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/03/g-eazy-cyhi-the-prynce-mansionzs-new-album/|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Digital Druglord'' and ''Cybersex''===\nOn January 29, 2017, he posted the track \"Make Daddy Proud\", which was a remix of Jeremy Zucker's \"Heavy\", on his SoundCloud page. The track was later confirmed to be the next promotional single for his third studio album ''[[Digital Druglord]]''. On March 17, 2017, Blackbear released the lead single for the album, titled \"Do Re Mi\".<ref name=\"do re mi\">{{Citation|title=blackbear \u2013 do re mi|url=https://genius.com/Blackbear-do-re-mi-lyrics|language=en|accessdate=2017-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2017, shortly before the release of ''Digital Druglord'', Blackbear released a short acoustic EP titled ''Salt'' on his SoundCloud. ''Digital Druglord'' was released on April 20, 2017, featuring the single \"Do Re Mi\" along with promotional singles \"If I Could I Would Feel Nothing\" and \"Make Daddy Proud\".<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/digital-druglord/id1216872048</ref> In an interview with Vice's music channel [[Vice (magazine)|Noisey]], he revealed that he wrote ''Digital Druglord'' while in the hospital based on his experiences with alcohol and drugs. He states that the cover art for the album, a woman with pill bottles attached to her chest, is not to glorify the use of pharmaceuticals, but because he now has to take prescription drugs to stay alive due to his illness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/pa3wvz/blackbear-interview-cybersex-2017|title=blackbear Is Extremely Famous, Even If You Don't Know Who He Is|date=2017-11-14|work=Noisey|access-date=2018-06-24|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2017, he signed a 10 million dollar distribution deal with [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] that gave the label the rights to ''Digital Druglord'' and the following studio album and their respective singles.<ref name=\"complex\" />\n\nOn August 18, 2017, Blackbear announced his next project, a mixtape named ''[[Cybersex (album)|Cybersex]]''. The name ''Cybersex'' comes from Blackbear's infatuation with the internet. In an interview with [[Pigeons & Planes]], he talks about how the internet is why he is here and how cybersex was the first form of sexting. He states how he finds the internet interesting and how you can now fall asleep with your loved one in another country, due to technology.<ref name=\":0\" /> He released a song on SoundCloud in September 2017 titled \"froze over\". The track was written and produced by Good Intent and Blackbear and it would later appear in ''Cybersex'' as a two part interlude titled \"thursday/froze over\". On October 6, 2017, a song titled \"Playboy Shit\", which features rapper Lil Aaron, was released on Blackbear's [[Pornhub|PornHub]] account and confirmed to be a part of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/playboy-s-t-feat-lil-aaron-single/id1293942675|title=Playboy S**t (feat. lil aaron) - Single by blackbear on Apple Music|website=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=2017-10-14}}</ref> On October 20, 2017, Blackbear released the single \"Bright Pink Tims\" featuring [[Cam'ron]]. This day also marked the first day of his tour in support of Fall Out Boy's [[The Mania Tour|Mania Tour]], running until November 18. On November 27, 2017, Musto's 27th birthday, ''Cybersex'' was released.\n\nOn April 26, 2018, \"About You\", a song written by Linkin Park's [[Mike Shinoda]] regarding the death of his bandmate [[Chester Bennington]], was released featuring Blackbear.<ref>{{cite web|title=LINKIN PARK's MIKE SHINODA: 'I Had Terrible Days, And Now I Have Less Bad Days'|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/linkin-parks-mike-shinoda-i-had-terrible-days-and-now-i-have-less-bad-days/|website=BLABBERMOUTH.NET|accessdate=12 May 2018|date=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2018, Blackbear released his single titled \"the 1\", produced by FRND.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blackbear Is Back With \"The 1\" |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/blackbear-is-back-with-the-1-new-song.1980033.html |website=HotNewHipHop |accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019: ''Anonymous'' and ''Sad But Chillin''===\n\nIn February 2019, Blackbear said he would be releasing a single per week until April 26, which is when his fourth studio album would be released. On Valentine's Day 2019, he released his single \"1 SIDED LOVE\". On February 20, he released his single \"HIGH1X\". On March 13, he released his single \"SWEAR TO GOD\" during [[Zane Lowe]]'s transmission on [[Beats 1]].\n\nApril 26, 2019, he released the full album, ''[[Anonymous (Blackbear album)|Anonymous]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inkedmag.com/original-news/exclusive-blackbear-dishes-on-his-upcoming-album|title=Exclusive: Blackbear Dishes on His Upcoming Album|last=Preston|first=Devon|website=Tattoo Ideas, Artists and Models|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|title=ANONYMOUS by blackbear|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/anonymous/1453250142|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> This album is his longest album yet, containing 18 tracks lasting a total of 51 minutes. Along with the release of this album, he posted a photo on Instagram with a caption discussing his gratefulness of a second chance after his health complications at age 27, and he discusses how meaningful this album is to him. \n\nOn August 23, 2019, he released the lead single \"[[Hot Girl Bummer]]\" from his upcoming fifth studio album \"Sad But Chillin\".<ref>https://www.altpress.com/news/blackblack-hot-girl-bummer-video/</ref>\nOn November 13, 2019, Blackbear released the one off single \"[[Tongue Tied (Marshmello, Yungblud and Blackbear song)|Tongue Tied]]\", with American producer [[Marshmello]] and English singer [[Yungblud]].\nOn January 16, 2020, he released second single \"Me & Ur Ghost\".\n\n== Producing and songwriting ==\nIn addition to his own music, Musto has produced and written for many popular artists. He has collaborated with numerous musical artists such as [[Marc E. Bassy]], [[Justin Bieber]], [[G-Eazy]], [[Mike Posner]], [[Maejor Ali]], [[Palisades (band)|Palisades]], [[Machine Gun Kelly (rapper)|Machine Gun Kelly]], [[Rick Ross]], [[Cam\u2019ron]], [[2 Chainz]], [[Mod Sun]], [[Rivers Cuomo]], [[Childish Gambino]], [[Billie Eilish]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Mike Shinoda]], Tiny Meat Gang, and [[Jacob Sartorius]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pop-buzz.com/just-music/who-is-blackbear/|title=Who Is blackbear And Why Do Your Faves Love Him?|website=Pop Buzz}}</ref>\nHe co-wrote \"[[Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)|Boyfriend]]\" by Justin Bieber, alongside Mike Posner, which debuted at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Justin Bieber's 'Boyfriend' Debuts at No. 2 on Hot 100|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/497102/justin-biebers-boyfriend-debuts-at-no-2-on-hot-100|website=Billboard|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.warnerchappell.com/song-details/WW%20010026937%2000/2bcabefc-9461-4f97-9294-160347dafb3d|website=www.warnerchappell.com|access-date=2019-03-06|title=Boyfriend - Warner/Chappell Music}}</ref> He also produced the title track from G-Eazy's album These Things Happen, as well as featuring on the album.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Producing and Songwriting Credits\n!TITLE\n!ARTIST\n!YEAR\n!ROLE\n|-\n|\"End of the Road\"\n|[[Machine Gun Kelly (musician)|Machine Gun Kelly]]\n|2012\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Boyfriend\"\n|[[Justin Bieber]]\n|2012\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|\"These Things Happen\"\n|[[G-Eazy]]\n|2014\n|Songwriter/producer<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Look Up\"\n|[[Mod Sun]]\n|2015\n|Producer<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Mind Games\"\n|[[Palisades (band)|Palisades]]\n|2015\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Sorry For Now\"\n|[[Linkin Park]]\n|2017\n|Producer<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|\"talk is overrated\"\n|[[Jeremy Zucker]]\n|2017\n|Songwriter<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"About You\"\n|[[Mike Shinoda]]\n|2018\n|Songwriter/producer<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/blackbear-mn0003007622/credits|title=Blackbear {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nMusto was born in [[Pittston, Pennsylvania]] and moved to [[Daytona Beach, Florida]] as a child.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Deiter|first1=Olivia|title=Blackbear|url=https://shsthetorch.com/22355/showcase/blackbear/|website=the Torch|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"complex\"/> Musto was raised in [[Palm Coast, Florida]].<ref name=\"reverbnation.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/pa3wvz/blackbear-interview-cybersex-2017|title=blackbear Is Extremely Famous, Even If You Don't Know Who He Is|date=2017-11-14|work=Noisey|access-date=2017-12-03|language=en-us}}</ref> He moved to [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] and then [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] in his late teens.\n\nIn April 2016, he was hospitalized and diagnosed with chronic pancreatitis due to excessive alcohol use. During his time in the hospital, he wrote his album \"Digital Druglord\" and took this time to become sober.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blackbear Looked Death in The Eyes And Released His Best Album to Date |url=https://www.hypefresh.co/blackbear-looked-death-in-the-eyes-and-released-his-best-album-to-date/ |website=Hypefresh Inc |accessdate=23 January 2020 |date=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=How a Near-Death Experience Helped blackbear Make His Most Successful Album Yet |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7785135/blackbear-digital-druglord-album-interview |website=Billboard |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref> In November 2018, Musto collaborated with the brand [[PopSockets]] and donated 50% of the proceeds of his branded products to Mission: Cure, a non-profit dedicated to finding a cure for chronic pancreatitis.<ref>{{cite web |title=im 1 of many w/ chronic pancreatitis mission : cure are closer everyday to finding a cure. donating half to them!http://popsockets.com/pages/blackbear\u00a0pic.twitter.com/2wT20pp5Dn |url=https://twitter.com/iamblackbear/status/1063566734815195136?lang=en |website=Twitter |accessdate=23 January 2020 |language=en |date=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2019, Musto announced that he and his girlfriend Michele Maturo were expecting their first child in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shoemaker |first1=Whitney |title=blackbear and Michele Maturo announce pregnancy |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/blackbear-michele-maturo-pregnancy-baby-boy/ |website=Alternative Press |accessdate=4 October 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref> On January 29, 2020, the couple announced the birth of their son, Midnight Thomas Musto, born on January 26, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=blackbear on Instagram: \u201cMIDNIGHT THOMAS MUSTO IS HERE im a papa im a daddy!!!!!!!! omg omg i havent stopp crying\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B76uG3unKVS/ |website=Instagram |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Michele on Instagram: \u201cMidnight Thomas Musto is here + healthy & weighs 7lb 3oz & arrived January 26th. No other way to describe how I feel besides perfect.\u2026\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B76l_XYnA54/ |website=Instagram |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Blackbear discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''Deadroses'' (2015)\n* ''Help'' (2015)\n* ''[[Digital Druglord]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Anonymous (Blackbear album)|Anonymous]]'' (2019)\n* ''Sad But Chillin''<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8ZiK0CHY0n/|title=changed name of album to sad but chillin|accessdate=March 4, 2020|via=[[Instagram]]}}</ref> (2020)\n'''Collaborative albums'''\n* ''Hotel Motel'' {{small|(with [[Mod Sun]])}} (2016)\n* ''[[Mansionz]]'' {{small|(with [[Mike Posner]])}} (2017)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{Blackbear}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American indie pop musicians]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pop rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Florida]]\n[[Catgeory:Singers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Trap musicians]]\n", "name_user": "144.138.204.62", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blackbear_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "When You Get a Little Lonely", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{For|the Nicolette Larson song|...Say When}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name        = When You Get a Little Lonely\n| type        = studio\n| artist      = [[Maureen McCormick]]\n| cover       = MaureenMcCormack111.jpg\n| border      = yes\n| alt         = The album cover for ''When You Get a Little Lonely''\n| released    = April 4, 1995\n| recorded    = 1994\u20131995\n| studio      = {{Flat list|\n* Nightingale Studios (Nashville)\n* Tempo Recording (Hollywood)\n}}\n| genre       = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length      = 34:41\n| label       = Phantom Hill\n| producer    = Barry Coffing (also [[Executive producer|exec.]])\n| misc        = {{Singles\n | name        = When You Get a Little Lonely\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = When You Get a Little Lonely\n | single1date = 1995\n | single2     = Tell Mama\n | single2date = September 1995\n}}\n}}\n'''''When You Get a Little Lonely''''' is the debut studio album by American actress and singer [[Maureen McCormick]]. It was released on April 4, 1995, through the [[Record label|label]] Phantom Hill. After playing [[Marcia Brady]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'', she was offered a solo record deal in the mid-1970s but rejected the offer to attend school. McCormick had previously recorded four albums as part of ''The Brady Bunch'' and a duet album with her co-star [[Christopher Knight (actor)|Christopher Knight]]. In 1994, she signed with her brother's record label, Phantom Hill, and recorded ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and [[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]]. Barry Coffing was the [[executive producer]] and arranged and produced all the songs. McCormick wanted to fuse genres into the album's overall [[Country music|country]] sound.\n\nThe album received mainly negative reviews; some reviewers were critical of McCormick's choice to record country music. She promoted it through live performances and [[Compact disc|CD]] signings. Its title track and \"Tell Mama\" were released as singles. ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was re-released in 2008 as a [[Circuit City]] exclusive. Since the album's release, McCormick has continued to perform country music and has participated in the [[reality television]] show [[Gone Country (TV series)|''Gone Country'']]. In a 2008 interview, McCormick said she was disappointed by restrictions to the recording process and wished she had written at least one song for it. ''When You Get A Little Lonely'' is her only album as a solo artist.\n\n== Background and recording ==\n[[File:Marcia, Marcia, Marcia.png|thumb|left|McCormick in a 1971 ''The Brady Bunch'' promotional photo|alt=A 1971 photograph of Maureen McCormick as part of a 1971 ''The Brady Bunch'' promotional campaign.]]\n\n[[Maureen McCormick]] first rose to prominence while playing [[Marcia Brady]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Brady Bunch]]''. She entered the entertainment industry by performing [[jingle]]s; at the age of 10, she sang for a [[Kellogg's]] advertisement.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/145566910/|url-access=subscription|title=It's A Sunshine Day|last=Voger|first=Mark|date=May 21, 1995|work=[[Asbury Park Press]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> As a part of ''The Brady Bunch'' cast, she released four albums, the first of which she recorded at age 15. McCormick also released a duet album with her television co-star [[Christopher Knight (actor)|Christopher Knight]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Source4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/maureen-mccormick-s-top-5-country-music-moments-88966|title=Maureen McCormick's top 5 country music moments|last=Miller|first=Victoria|date=September 8, 2015|publisher=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925093947/http://www.axs.com/maureen-mccormick-s-top-5-country-music-moments-88966|archivedate=September 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Victoria Miller, writing for the digital marketing platform [[AXS (company)|AXS]], considered her music with ''The Brady Bunch'' [[bubblegum pop]]; she cited the 1973 song \"[[It's a Sunshine Day]]\" as an example.<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\nMcCormick, however, identified with [[country music]], saying she listened to the genre while growing up on her father's horse ranch.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> A \"country-tinged tune\" entitled \"Little Bird\" was among the songs on her album with Knight.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> When discussing her attraction to country, she said: \"I love songs that tell stories. Words to me are the most important thing.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperStory\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/177000915/|url-access=subscription|title=Maureen McCormick joins country music bunch|last=|first=|date=January 26, 1994|work=[[Florida Today]]|access-date=May 22, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> After ''The Brady Bunch'' ended in 1974, a company offered McCormick a record deal to record a country album, describing it as her \"natural sound\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She rejected the offer to return to college and pursue a more \"normal life\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Orlando1\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-05-28/news/9506010699_1_maureen-mccormick-marcia-brady-brady-bunch|title=Maureen McCormick|last=McKechnie|first=Gary|date=May 28, 1995|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029051349/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-05-28/news/9506010699_1_maureen-mccormick-marcia-brady-brady-bunch|archivedate=October 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2008 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' interview, McCormick said she regretted not taking the deal, saying \"I think it would've been interesting to see where it would've gone.\"<ref name=\"EW1\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2008/03/03/a-chat-with-mau/|title=A chat with Maureen McCormick|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|date=March 3, 2008|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080512025450/http://popwatch.ew.com:80/popwatch/2008/03/a-chat-with-mau.html|archivedate=May 12, 2008|url-status=live|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In 1994, McCormick signed a recording contract with her brother's [[Record label|label]] Phantom Hill.<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /><ref name=\"Source7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/maureen-mccormick-p47115|last=Cooper|first=Tracie|title=Factsheet|website=[[AllMovie]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmovie.com/artist/maureen-mccormick-p47115|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During a 1995 [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] interview, she said; \"Music has always been my first love, and I've been waiting a long time for this opportunity. The wait just makes you stronger.\"<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\">{{cite journal|last=Atwood|first=Brett|date=April 1, 1995|title=TV: A Help or Hindrance to Musicians?|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=%22Maureen+McCormick%22+%22Billboard%22#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20McCormick%22%20%22Billboard%22&f=false|url-status=live|volume=107|issue=13|pages=8|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://books.google.com/books?id=6gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=%22Maureen+McCormick%22+%22Billboard%22&source=bl&ots=8zu947wzJV&sig=uRUHqu8nwKaBJCvAX6g-7urhBm4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja4ZbIxdbbAhVFrFMKHd8aCSIQ6AEIdDAT#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20McCormick%22%20%22Billboard%22&f=false|archivedate=June 15, 2018|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\nMcCormick recorded the album in 1994 and 1995 in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and [[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]].<ref name=\"Book1\">[[When You Get a Little Lonely#Peppiatt2004|Peppiatt (2004)]]</ref><ref name=\"Source1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134|title=AllMusic Review by Pemberton Roach|last=Roach|first=Pemberton|website=[[AllMusic]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134|archive-date=June 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview1\" /> While in Nashville, she went to [[Music Row]] to find inspiration; after returning to California, she selected her favorite songs to include on ''When You Get a Little Lonely''.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She had considered hundreds of songs before deciding on the eleven in the final track listing.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> The [[executive producer]] Barry Coffing arranged and produced all of the tracks.<ref name=\"Source0\">{{cite AV media notes|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|date=April 4, 1995|others=[[Maureen McCormick]]|type=Inlay cover|publisher=Phantom Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"Coffing1\">{{cite book|title=When you get a little lonely|publisher=[[WorldCat]]|df=mdy-all|oclc = 32606771}}</ref> A 1994 episode of ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' included portions of the Nashville recording sessions.<ref name=\"Interview1\">{{cite interview|last=McCormick|first=Maureen|subject-link=Maureen McCormick|interviewer=[[Mary Hart]]|title=The Hart Files|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E7PWHDdyOww|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|publisher=[[Paramount Domestic Television]]|location=United States|date=March 8, 1994}}</ref> McCormick described the album as \"[her] debut singing\"; when asked about her past music career, she said, \"Well, those weren't solo songs. They were the Brady kids.\u00a0And that's not me anymore.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperSunTimes2\">{{cite news|url=|title='Brady Kid' Has Grown-up Advice: Maureen McCormick Touts Birth Control|last=Kim|first=Jae-Ha|date=March 10, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|location=|via=}}</ref> While completing ''When You Get a Little Lonely'', McCormick was offered a [[cameo role]] on ''[[The Brady Bunch Movie]]'' (1995) but turned it down to focus on the album.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She had also been approached the previous year about the same cameo but was unable to accept because she was playing [[Betty Rizzo]] in a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of the musical [[Grease (musical)|''Grease'']].<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Newspaper3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/135988293/|url-access=subscription|title=Here's the story of a girl named Brady|last=Gutierrez|first=Lisa|date=July 21, 1995|work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Composition and sound ==\nMcCormick described ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"country crossover\" and said, \"We tried to get some different styles, one that's upbeat, then there's a bluesy, jazzy, sexy song, then a commercial feeling\".<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> She listed [[Linda Ronstadt]], [[James Taylor]], [[Mary Chapin Carpenter]], and the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]] as her influences.<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> Discussing the song selection process, McCormick said she tried to \"get some different sounds together and have an album with a lot of a variety\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> [[AllMusic]]'s Pemberton Roach referred to the album as a \"completely straight-ahead modern Nashville country record\",<ref name=\"Source1\" /> while ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Alanna Nash described it as [[country pop]], citing its release as part of a trend of Hollywood celebrities recording music in Nashville.<ref name=\"Source5\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1995/04/21/when-you-get-little-lonely/|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|last=Nash|first=Alanna|date=April 21, 1995|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120085719/http://www.ew.com/article/1995/04/21/when-you-get-little-lonely|archivedate=November 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The instruments used on ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' include [[pedal steel guitar]], fiddle, and piano, which a [[People (magazine)|''People'']] magazine contributor called \"all the twanging tools of the [country music] trade\", and wrote that McCormick adopted a \"Nashville accent\".<ref name=\"Source6\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-when-you-get-a-little-lonely-vol-43-no-18/|title=Picks and Pans Review: When You Get a Little Lonely|date=May 8, 1995|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-when-you-get-a-little-lonely-vol-43-no-18/|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe album credits include \"[[Music City]]'s finest\" ([[David Hungate]], J.D. Maness, and [[Larry Knechtel]]) and \"the usual suspects\" ([[Troy Seals]], [[Nicolette Larson]], and [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]).<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Mike Hughes, writing for ''[[The Times Herald]]'', described McCormick's [[Cover (music)|cover]] of [[Nicolette Larson]]'s 1985 single \"When You Get a Little Lonely\" as \"an [[uptempo|up-tempo]], [[Dancehall|dance-hall]] tune in current country style\".<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/211737147/|url-access=subscription|title=Robert Reed's influence lives in ''Brady'' sequels|last=Hughes|first=Mike|date=May 24, 1995|work=[[The Times Herald]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> She also covered [[Rena Gaile]]'s 1996 single \"[[Cloud of Dust]]\",<ref name=\"Source0\" /> and recorded a version of [[the Crickets]]' 1957 single \"[[Oh, Boy! (The Crickets song)|Oh, Boy!]]\" at the suggestion of [[Bread (band)|Bread]] front man [[David Gates]]. McCormick said \"Oh Boy!\" was her daughter's favorite song from the album.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" />\n\nLisa Gutierrez, writing for ''[[Democrat and Chronicle]]'', described ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as a \"truly grown-up work\" in comparison to her performance as Marcia Brady.<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /> McCormick sings about sex using lyrics such as, \"He does me wrong, he does me right. He does me crazy in the middle of the night.\"<ref name=\"Newspaper2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/176530073/|url-access=subscription|title=''When You Get A Little Lonely''|last=Seline|first=Anita M.|date=June 1, 1995|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Other lyrics include \"don't bury me on the love prairie\".<ref name=\"Newsday\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/tube-stars-who-laid-down-tracks-1.2548138|title=Tube stars who laid down tracks|last=Bubbeo|first=Daniel|date=December 17, 2010|work=[[Newsday]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615234957/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/tube-stars-who-laid-down-tracks-1.2548138|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She also addresses \"loss [and] the Wild West\" in the songs.<ref name=\"Time\" /> American singer-songwriter [[Wayland Patton]] appears as a guest artist on \"We Must Have Done Something Right\".<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was released through Phantom Hill on April 4, 1995, on [[audio CD|CD]] and [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] formats.<ref name=\"Coffing1\" /><ref name=\"Source3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/releases|title=Releases|website=[[AllMusic]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/releases|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> McCormick uploaded portions of the songs to her official website.<ref name=\"HighBeam1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-507289541.html|url-access=subscription|title=The Vagina Monologues: Of course Marcia had one; An interview with Maureen McCormick|date=February 4, 2003|work=[[Santa Fe Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-507289541.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"FabCD1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/how-to-write-a-sitcom-2132814|title=How To Write a Sitcom|last=Shulman|first=Dave|date=December 15, 2000|work=[[LA Weekly]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20010129093300/http://laweekly.com/ink/01/04/sitegeist-shulman.shtml|archivedate=January 29, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> McCormick, who was 38 at the time of the release, wanted to distance herself from the \"perpetual-teenager image\" of Marcia Brady.<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\" /> The packaging does not reference ''The Brady Bunch'';<ref name=\"Source1\" /> it includes a picture of a two-year-old McCormick dressed as a [[cowgirl]].<ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> The cover, however, bore a sticker saying \"Marcia Marcia Marcia\", which McCormick said was done by a public relations company and described its inclusion as \"a ''big'' mistake\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" />\n\nMcCormick told ''Billboard'' she felt \"optimistic\" that [[country radio]] would accept her music.<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\" /> During a 1995 interview, she said people, particularly [[DJ]]s, enjoyed the album and her voice; ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''{{'s}} Gary McKechnie wrote that it \"seem[ed] to be popular with country music fans\".<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> The song \"When You Get a Little Lonely\" was the [[lead single]] and promoted through a [[music video]].<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\" /> The video was shown on the 1995 [[television special]] ''Brady Bunch Home Movies''.<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\" /><ref name=\"NewspaperStorm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178196364/|url-access=subscription|title=''The Brady Bunch'' and ''Laverne & Shirley'' get nostalgia treatment|last=Storm|first=Jonathan|date=August 16, 1995|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> \"Tell Mama\" was released in September 1995 as the second single.<ref name=\"NewspaperFried\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/275713505/|url-access=subscription|title=National Catfish Month survey says consumers like it fried|last=|first=|date=August 16, 1995|work=[[Clarksdale Press Register]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was made available as a [[Digital download (music)|digital download]] on [[Apple Music]], but it was later removed from the platform.<ref name=\"DigitalDownload1\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely/260546168|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|website=[[Apple Music]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615233727/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely/260546168|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Record label Building re-released the album as an exclusive for [[Circuit City]] in 2008.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> It is McCormick's only album as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Biopgraphy1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/maureen-mccormick-21273345|title=Maureen McCormick Biography|date=August 31, 2016|work=Biography.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323140142/https://www.biography.com/people/maureen-mccormick-21273345|archivedate=March 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1994 ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' report, McCormick planned to promote ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' with a tour.<ref name=\"NewspaperSunTimes2\" /> She held album signings in 1995 at a Hollywood [[Virgin Megastores|Virgin Megastore]], the [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] [[record store]] Peaches Music & Video, and a [[Henrietta, New York|Henrietta]] [[Media Play]].<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /><ref name=\"HighBeam2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25001230.html|url-access=subscription|title=Hot Tips Y'All Should Hear That Brady Gal Sing|date=April 24, 1995|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25001230.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"Orlando2\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-04-17/news/9504170063_1_marsha-brady-brady-bunch-peaches-music|title=Who: Maureen McCormick, also known as Marsha Brady from...|date=May 17, 1995|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016150206/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-04-17/news/9504170063_1_marsha-brady-brady-bunch-peaches-music|archivedate=October 16, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of the Henrietta event, Media Play held a \"''Brady Bunch'' look-alike contest\".<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /> McCormick promoted the album by performing at [[Lake Compounce]], an amusement park in Bristol and Southington, Connecticut, on July 2, 1995.<ref name=\"NewspaperPerformances\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/176664069/|url-access=subscription|title=Marsha! Marsha! Marsha!|last=|first=|date=June 29, 1995|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> On October 21, 1995, she performed during an [[Indianapolis Ice]] game against the [[Detroit Vipers]]. She also signed autographs during the game's intermission as part of a \"Brady Bunch Night\".<ref name=\"Newspaper6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/313324188/|url-access=subscription|title='Bunch' of fun is expected when 'Marcia' joins the Ice|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1995|work=[[Indianapolis News]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> The following year, she sang at the Palmdale Playhouse in [[Palmdale, California]].<ref name=\"HighBeam3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25037832.html|url-access=subscription|title=Palmdale Playhouse Opens '96 with Varied Fare|last=Thacker|first=Karen|date=January 8, 1996|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211423/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25037832.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In August 2001, McCormick appeared alongside her ''The Brady Bunch'' co-stars on the game show [[The Weakest Link (U.S. game show)|''The Weakest Link'']]. On his official website, [[Barry Williams (actor)|Barry Williams]], who played [[Greg Brady (Brady Bunch)|Greg Brady]], held a competition in which viewers could win prizes, one of which was a copy of ''When You Get a Little Lonely'', for guessing the winner of ''The Weakest Link'' correctly.<ref name=\"Newspaper7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/279195610/|url-access=subscription|title='Brady Bunch' cast reunites to compete on NBC's 'Weakest Link'|last=|first=|date=August 25, 2001|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|1.5|5}}<ref name=\"Source1\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|1|4}}<ref name=\"Newspaper5\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = F<ref name=\"Source5\" />\n| rev4 = ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''\n| rev4score = D\u2212<ref name=\"Time\" />\n}}\n''When You Get a Little Lonely'' received mainly negative reviews from critics. Some commentators recommended it for fans of ''The Brady Bunch''.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> Pemberton Roach described McCormick as a \"competent singer\" with enthusiasm but said her [[upper register]] was \"a little screechy at times\". Roach cited \"Cloud of Dust\" as a highlight but was less positive about the album as a whole and said it \"sounds like a well-produced L.A. songwriter demo\".<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Despite praising the song selection, ''[[Hartford Courant]]''{{'s}} Anita M. Seline criticized McCormick's voice, specifically on her \"tepid\" version of \"Oh Boy!\".<ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> A ''People'' writer suggested McCormick record pop music or covers of 1970s [[Top 40]] songs because \"kitschy stuff, after all, has a remarkable shelf life\". The reviewer said she \"doesn't bring much conviction to the material\" but her voice has a \"sweet, rather pure timbre&nbsp;... It's a very Brady sort of voice.\"<ref name=\"Source6\" /> Kathleen Adams and Lina Lofaro, writing for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' criticized McCormick's voice and said she \"shows scant vocal or emotional range and her backup musicians follow suit\".<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite journal|date=May 8, 1995|title=It didn't stop with William Shatner|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|volume=145|issue=19|pages=40|last1=Adams|first1=Kathleen|last2=Lofaro|first2=Lina|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators were critical of McCormick's decision to record country music. Alanna Nash panned ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"the most manufactured of country pop\" and criticized McCormick for singing with \"the overwrought exuberance of a high school variety show contestant\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''{{'s}} Miriam Longino wrote that she \"can carry a tune\" and that the album has the \"slickest arrangements and studio musicians\", but she largely dismissed it as \"a contrived attempt to cash in on country's popularity\". Longino said McCormick's interpretation of country music was inauthentic, writing, \"A pair of [[Tony Lama Boots|Tony Lama boots]] cannot transform this California actress into [[Patsy Cline]]\".<ref name=\"Newspaper5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/403240472/|url-access=subscription|title=''When You Get A Little Lonely''|last=Longino|first=Miriam|date=April 29, 1995|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A ''[[St. Cloud Times]]'' reviewer criticized her for \"tr[ying] her hand at country and go[ing] nowhere\".<ref name=\"Newspaper4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/225993301/|url-access=subscription|title=Country music's surge slows down in 1995|last=|first=|date=December 28, 1995|work=[[St. Cloud Times]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A ''Time'' contributor dismissed ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"new country curbed and gutted\".<ref name=\"Time\" /> In a 2010 ''[[Newsday]]'' article, Daniel Bubbeo wrote, \"it's doubtful [McCormick] caused [[Reba McEntire]] to have any sleepless nights\".<ref name=\"Newsday\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Maureen McCormick Maui crop.PNG|thumb|McCormick at a 2009 book signing|alt=A 2009 photograph of Maureen McCormick.]]\n\nIn a 2008 interview, McCormick said she was disappointed by the recording process for ''When You Get a Little Lonely'': \"I kinda felt like it wasn't done the right way. There are certain rules in Nashville, and my album didn't really follow them.\" She wished the process had been \"more organic\" and that she could have written at least one of the songs.<ref name=\"EW1\" />\n\nAccording to a 2015 AXS article, McCormick has \"long been associated with country music\", including her portrayal of [[Barbara Mandrell]] in the 1997 [[television film]] ''Get to the Heart: The Barbara Mandrell Story''.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> She [[Lip sync|lip-synced]] to Mandrell's music,<ref name=\"NewspaperPalm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/133287603/|url-access=subscription|title=Stretching It: From Marcia Brady to Barbara Mandrell|last=Thompson|first=Kevin D.|date=September 26, 1997|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> saying; \"Really, in a piece like this, you're playing that person. I would never be able to sound like her.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperKoko\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/2774745/|url-access=subscription|title=Barbara, Barbara, Barbara|last=Waldon|first=David Brian|date=September 15, 1997|work=[[Kokomo Tribune]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Also in 1997, McCormick was an opening act for [[Clint Black]] and [[Faith Hill]], and performed with [[Hal Ketchum]] and the [[Confederate Railroad]].<ref name=\"NewspaperPalm\" /><ref name=\"NewspaperDailyNews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/477521652/|url-access=subscription|title=There's a Song in Their Arts|last=Schulman|first=Sandra|date=August 31, 1997|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nMcCormick appeared in the music video for [[Brad Paisley]]'s 2007 song \"[[Online (song)|Online]]\".<ref name=\"Source4\" /> The following year, she competed on the first season of the reality television show [[Gone Country (TV series)|''Gone Country'']];<ref name=\"Source4\" /> as the prize, [[John Rich]] would produce the winner's song, and it would be sent to radio.<ref name=\"EW1\" /> McCormick said it was a \"lifelong dream to have a song on the radio\".<ref name=\"Source4\" /> In March 2008, [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]] was announced as the winner of the season.<ref name=\"CMT1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmtpress.com/press-release/julio-iglesias-jr-tapped-by-host-john-rich-as-cmts-hit-series-gone-country-winner/|title=Julio Iglesias, Jr Tapped by Host John Rich as CMT's Hit Series ''Gone Country'' Winner|date=March 10, 2008|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Access Hollywood]]''{{'s}} executive producer Rob Silverstein hired McCormick as a red-carpet reporter for the [[2008 CMT Music Awards]] after seeing her on ''Gone Country''.<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits are taken from the booklet of ''When You Get a Little Lonely''. Barry Coffing produced all of the songs.<ref name=\"Source0\" />\n\n{{Tracklist\n| total_length    = 34:41\n| title1 = When You Get a Little Lonely\n| writer1 = [[Nicolette Larson]], Wendy Waldman, [[Josh Leo]]\n| length1 = 4:03\n| title2 = I'd Have to Call It Love\n| writer2 = [[Robert Ellis Orrall]]\n| length2 = 3:17\n| title3 = Tell Mama\n| writer3 = Barry Coffing\n| length3 = 3:03\n| title4 = Some Somebody\n| writer4 = [[Troy Seals]], [[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]], Rhonda Gunn\n| length4 = 3:28\n| title5 = We Must Have Done Something Right\n| note5 = featuring [[Wayland Patton]]\n| writer5 = Marc Beeson, [[Liz Hengber]]\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = [[Cloud of Dust]]\n| writer6 = [[Judy Rodman]], Tom Damphier\n| length6 = 3:15\n| title7 = Go West\n| writer7 = [[Gretchen Peters]]\n| length7 = 2:53\n| title8 = [[Oh, Boy! (The Crickets song)|Oh, Boy!]]\n| writer8 = [[Norman Petty]], Bill Tilghman, Sonny West\n| length8 = 3:03\n| title9 = Might as Well Be Me\n| writer9 = [[Pam Tillis]], [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]\n| length9 = 2:52\n| title10 = I Do But I Don't\n| writer10 = [[Foster & Lloyd|Bill Lloyd]], Mark Irwin\n| length10 = 2:37\n| title11 = I Can't Say\n| writer11 = George Teren, Bob Regan\n| length11 = 2:41\n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nThe following credits were adapted from the booklet of ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' and AllMusic:<ref name=\"Source0\" /><ref name=\"Source2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/credits|title=Credits|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/credits|archivedate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* Richard Abramson&nbsp;\u2013 stylist\n* Osama Afifi&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* [[Barry Beckett]]&nbsp;\u2013 organ (Hammond)\n* Marc Beeson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Chris Bellman&nbsp;\u2013 mixing\n* Mike Botts&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* Carter Bradley&nbsp;\u2013 make-up\n* Valerie Carter&nbsp;\u2013 vocals (background)\n* Barry Coffing&nbsp;\u2013 arranger, composer, piano, producer, vocals (background)\n* Jim Cox&nbsp;\u2013 piano\n* Tom Damphier&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Dan Dugmore&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, pedal steel\n* David Eaton&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n* [[Kenny Edwards]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals (background)\n* Jim Gaines&nbsp;\u2013 photography\n* Nicola Goode&nbsp;\u2013 cover design\n* Rhonda Gunn&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Liz Hengber&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Steve Hill&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* Randy Howard&nbsp;\u2013 fiddle, mandolin\n* Chris Hufford&nbsp;\u2013 engineer, mixing\n* David Hungate&nbsp;\u2013 bass\n* Mark Irwin&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Larry Knechtel]]&nbsp;\u2013 piano\n* Craig Krampf&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* Bob Krusen&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n* Nicolette Larson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Albert Lee]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* Josh Leo&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Bill Lloyd&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Jay Dee Maness&nbsp;\u2013 pedal steel\n* Maureen McCormick&nbsp;\u2013 primary artist, vocals\n* Gary Nicholson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Robert Ellis Orrall&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* David Pascal&nbsp;\u2013 art direction\n* Wayland Patton&nbsp;\u2013 performer, primary artist, vocals\n* Gretchen Peters&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Norman Petty]]&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Bob Regan&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Mike Reid&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Judy Rodman&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Troy Seals]]&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Leland Sklar]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass\n* Hans J. Spurkel&nbsp;\u2013 photography\n* George Teren&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Bill Tilghman&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Pam Tillis]]&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Wendy Waldman]]&nbsp;\u2013 composer, vocals (background)\n* Sonny West&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\"| United States\n| April 4, 1995\n| {{hlist|Cassette|CD}}\n| Phantom Hill<ref name=\"Coffing1\" /><ref name=\"Source3\" />\n|-\n| 1998\n| CD\n| Building<ref name=\"Source3\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs release|type=album|5166370|name=When You Get a Little Lonely}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:1995 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Maureen McCormick albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{For|the Nicolette Larson song|...Say When}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name        = When You Get a Little Lonely\n| type        = studio\n| artist      = [[Maureen McCormick]]\n| cover       = MaureenMcCormack111.jpg\n| border      = yes\n| alt         = The album cover for ''When You Get a Little Lonely''\n| released    = April 4, 1995\n| recorded    = 1994\u20131995\n| studio      = {{Flat list|\n* Nightingale Studios (Nashville)\n* Tempo Recording (Hollywood)\n}}\n| genre       = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length      = 34:41\n| label       = Phantom Hill\n| producer    = Barry Coffing (also [[Executive producer|exec.]])\n| misc        = {{Singles\n | name        = When You Get a Little Lonely\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = When You Get a Little Lonely\n | single1date = 1995\n | single2     = Tell Mama\n | single2date = September 1995\n}}\n}}\n'''''When You Get a Little Lonely''''' is the debut studio album by American actress and singer [[Maureen McCormick]]. It was released on April 4, 1995, through the [[Record label|label]] Phantom Hill. After playing [[Marcia Brady]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'', she was offered a solo record deal in the mid-1970s but rejected the offer to attend school. McCormick had previously recorded four albums as part of ''The Brady Bunch'' and a duet album with her co-star [[Christopher Knight (actor)|Christopher Knight]]. In 1994, she signed with her brother's record label, Phantom Hill, and recorded ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and [[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]]. Barry Coffing was the [[executive producer]] and arranged and produced all the songs. McCormick wanted to fuse genres into the album's overall [[Country music|country]] sound.\n\nThe album received mainly negative reviews; some reviewers were critical of McCormick's choice to record country music. She promoted it through live performances and [[Compact disc|CD]] signings. Its title track and \"Tell Mama\" were released as singles. ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was re-released in 2008 as a [[Circuit City]] exclusive. Since the album's release, McCormick has continued to perform country music and has participated in the [[reality television]] show [[Gone Country (TV series)|''Gone Country'']]. In a 2008 interview, McCormick said she was disappointed by restrictions to the recording process and wished she had written at least one song for it. ''When You Get A Little Lonely'' is her only album as a solo artist.\n\n== Background and recording ==\n[[File:Marcia, Marcia, Marcia.png|thumb|left|McCormick in a 1971 ''The Brady Bunch'' promotional photo|alt=A 1971 photograph of Maureen McCormick as part of a 1971 ''The Brady Bunch'' promotional campaign.]]\n\n[[Maureen McCormick]] first rose to prominence while playing [[Marcia Brady]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Brady Bunch]]''. She entered the entertainment industry by performing [[jingle]]s; at the age of 10, she sang for a [[Kellogg's]] advertisement.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/145566910/|url-access=subscription|title=It's A Sunshine Day|last=Voger|first=Mark|date=May 21, 1995|work=[[Asbury Park Press]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> As a part of ''The Brady Bunch'' cast, she released four albums, the first of which she recorded at age 15. McCormick also released a duet album with her television co-star [[Christopher Knight (actor)|Christopher Knight]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Source4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/maureen-mccormick-s-top-5-country-music-moments-88966|title=Maureen McCormick's top 5 country music moments|last=Miller|first=Victoria|date=September 8, 2015|publisher=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925093947/http://www.axs.com/maureen-mccormick-s-top-5-country-music-moments-88966|archivedate=September 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Victoria Miller, writing for the digital marketing platform [[AXS (company)|AXS]], considered her music with ''The Brady Bunch'' [[bubblegum pop]]; she cited the 1973 song \"[[It's a Sunshine Day]]\" as an example.<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\nMcCormick, however, identified with [[country music]], saying she listened to the genre while growing up on her father's horse ranch.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> A \"country-tinged tune\" entitled \"Little Bird\" was among the songs on her album with Knight.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> When discussing her attraction to country, she said: \"I love songs that tell stories. Words to me are the most important thing.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperStory\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/177000915/|url-access=subscription|title=Maureen McCormick joins country music bunch|last=|first=|date=January 26, 1994|work=[[Florida Today]]|access-date=May 22, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> After ''The Brady Bunch'' ended in 1974, a company offered McCormick a record deal to record a country album, describing it as her \"natural sound\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She rejected the offer to return to college and pursue a more \"normal life\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Orlando1\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-05-28/news/9506010699_1_maureen-mccormick-marcia-brady-brady-bunch|title=Maureen McCormick|last=McKechnie|first=Gary|date=May 28, 1995|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029051349/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-05-28/news/9506010699_1_maureen-mccormick-marcia-brady-brady-bunch|archivedate=October 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2008 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' interview, McCormick said she regretted not taking the deal, saying \"I think it would've been interesting to see where it would've gone.\"<ref name=\"EW1\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2008/03/03/a-chat-with-mau/|title=A chat with Maureen McCormick|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|date=March 3, 2008|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080512025450/http://popwatch.ew.com:80/popwatch/2008/03/a-chat-with-mau.html|archivedate=May 12, 2008|url-status=live|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In 1994, McCormick signed a recording contract with her brother's [[Record label|label]] Phantom Hill.<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /><ref name=\"Source7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/maureen-mccormick-p47115|last=Cooper|first=Tracie|title=Factsheet|website=[[AllMovie]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmovie.com/artist/maureen-mccormick-p47115|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During a 1995 [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] interview, she said; \"Music has always been my first love, and I've been waiting a long time for this opportunity. The wait just makes you stronger.\"<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\">{{cite journal|last=Atwood|first=Brett|date=April 1, 1995|title=TV: A Help or Hindrance to Musicians?|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=%22Maureen+McCormick%22+%22Billboard%22#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20McCormick%22%20%22Billboard%22&f=false|url-status=live|volume=107|issue=13|pages=8|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://books.google.com/books?id=6gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=%22Maureen+McCormick%22+%22Billboard%22&source=bl&ots=8zu947wzJV&sig=uRUHqu8nwKaBJCvAX6g-7urhBm4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja4ZbIxdbbAhVFrFMKHd8aCSIQ6AEIdDAT#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20McCormick%22%20%22Billboard%22&f=false|archivedate=June 15, 2018|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\nMcCormick recorded the album in 1994 and 1995 in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and [[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]].<ref name=\"Book1\">[[When You Get a Little Lonely#Peppiatt2004|Peppiatt (2004)]]</ref><ref name=\"Source1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134|title=AllMusic Review by Pemberton Roach|last=Roach|first=Pemberton|website=[[AllMusic]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134|archive-date=June 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview1\" /> While in Nashville, she went to [[Music Row]] to find inspiration; after returning to California, she selected her favorite songs to include on ''When You Get a Little Lonely''.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She had considered hundreds of songs before deciding on the eleven in the final track listing.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> The [[executive producer]] Barry Coffing arranged and produced all of the tracks.<ref name=\"Source0\">{{cite AV media notes|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|date=April 4, 1995|others=[[Maureen McCormick]]|type=Inlay cover|publisher=Phantom Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"Coffing1\">{{cite book|title=When you get a little lonely|publisher=[[WorldCat]]|df=mdy-all|oclc = 32606771}}</ref> A 1994 episode of ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' included portions of the Nashville recording sessions.<ref name=\"Interview1\">{{cite interview|last=McCormick|first=Maureen|subject-link=Maureen McCormick|interviewer=[[Mary Hart]]|title=The Hart Files|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E7PWHDdyOww|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|publisher=[[Paramount Domestic Television]]|location=United States|date=March 8, 1994}}</ref> McCormick described the album as \"[her] debut singing\"; when asked about her past music career, she said, \"Well, those weren't solo songs. They were the Brady kids.\u00a0And that's not me anymore.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperSunTimes2\">{{cite news|url=|title='Brady Kid' Has Grown-up Advice: Maureen McCormick Touts Birth Control|last=Kim|first=Jae-Ha|date=March 10, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|location=|via=}}</ref> While completing ''When You Get a Little Lonely'', McCormick was offered a [[cameo role]] on ''[[The Brady Bunch Movie]]'' (1995) but turned it down to focus on the album.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She had also been approached the previous year about the same cameo but was unable to accept because she was playing [[Betty Rizzo]] in a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of the musical [[Grease (musical)|''Grease'']].<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Newspaper3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/135988293/|url-access=subscription|title=Here's the story of a girl named Brady|last=Gutierrez|first=Lisa|date=July 21, 1995|work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Composition and sound ==\nMcCormick described ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"country crossover\" and said, \"We tried to get some different styles, one that's upbeat, then there's a bluesy, jazzy, sexy song, then a commercial feeling\".<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> She listed [[Linda Ronstadt]], [[James Taylor]], [[Mary Chapin Carpenter]], and the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]] as her influences.<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> Discussing the song selection process, McCormick said she tried to \"get some different sounds together and have an album with a lot of a variety\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> [[AllMusic]]'s Pemberton Roach referred to the album as a \"completely straight-ahead modern Nashville country record\",<ref name=\"Source1\" /> while ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Alanna Nash described it as [[country pop]], citing its release as part of a trend of Hollywood celebrities recording music in Nashville.<ref name=\"Source5\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1995/04/21/when-you-get-little-lonely/|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|last=Nash|first=Alanna|date=April 21, 1995|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120085719/http://www.ew.com/article/1995/04/21/when-you-get-little-lonely|archivedate=November 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The instruments used on ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' include [[pedal steel guitar]], fiddle, and piano, which a [[People (magazine)|''People'']] magazine contributor called \"all the twanging tools of the [country music] trade\", and wrote that McCormick adopted a \"Nashville accent\".<ref name=\"Source6\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-when-you-get-a-little-lonely-vol-43-no-18/|title=Picks and Pans Review: When You Get a Little Lonely|date=May 8, 1995|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-when-you-get-a-little-lonely-vol-43-no-18/|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe album credits include \"[[Music City]]'s finest\" ([[David Hungate]], J.D. Maness, and [[Larry Knechtel]]) and \"the usual suspects\" ([[Troy Seals]], [[Nicolette Larson]], and [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]).<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Mike Hughes, writing for ''[[The Times Herald]]'', described McCormick's [[Cover (music)|cover]] of [[Nicolette Larson]]'s 1985 single \"When You Get a Little Lonely\" as \"an [[uptempo|up-tempo]], [[Dancehall|dance-hall]] tune in current country style\".<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/211737147/|url-access=subscription|title=Robert Reed's influence lives in ''Brady'' sequels|last=Hughes|first=Mike|date=May 24, 1995|work=[[The Times Herald]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> She also covered [[Rena Gaile]]'s 1996 single \"[[Cloud of Dust]]\",<ref name=\"Source0\" /> and recorded a version of [[the Crickets]]' 1957 single \"[[Oh, Boy! (The Crickets song)|Oh, Boy!]]\" at the suggestion of [[Bread (band)|Bread]] front man [[David Gates]]. McCormick said \"Oh Boy!\" was her daughter's favorite song from the album.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" />\n\nLisa Gutierrez, writing for ''[[Democrat and Chronicle]]'', described ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as a \"truly grown-up work\" in comparison to her performance as Marcia Brady.<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /> McCormick sings about sex using lyrics such as, \"He does me wrong, he does me right. He does me crazy in the middle of the night.\"<ref name=\"Newspaper2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/176530073/|url-access=subscription|title=''When You Get A Little Lonely''|last=Seline|first=Anita M.|date=June 1, 1995|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Other lyrics include \"don't bury me on the love prairie\".<ref name=\"Newsday\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/tube-stars-who-laid-down-tracks-1.2548138|title=Tube stars who laid down tracks|last=Bubbeo|first=Daniel|date=December 17, 2010|work=[[Newsday]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615234957/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/tube-stars-who-laid-down-tracks-1.2548138|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She also addresses \"loss [and] the Wild West\" in the songs.<ref name=\"Time\" /> American singer-songwriter [[Wayland Patton]] appears as a guest artist on \"We Must Have Done Something Right\".<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was released through Phantom Hill on April 4, 1995, on [[audio CD|CD]] and [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] formats.<ref name=\"Coffing1\" /><ref name=\"Source3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/releases|title=Releases|website=[[AllMusic]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/releases|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> McCormick uploaded portions of the songs to her official website.<ref name=\"HighBeam1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-507289541.html|url-access=subscription|title=The Vagina Monologues: Of course Marcia had one; An interview with Maureen McCormick|date=February 4, 2003|work=[[Santa Fe Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-507289541.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"FabCD1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/how-to-write-a-sitcom-2132814|title=How To Write a Sitcom|last=Shulman|first=Dave|date=December 15, 2000|work=[[LA Weekly]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20010129093300/http://laweekly.com/ink/01/04/sitegeist-shulman.shtml|archivedate=January 29, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> McCormick, who was 38 at the time of the release, wanted to distance herself from the \"perpetual-teenager image\" of Marcia Brady.<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\" /> The packaging does not reference ''The Brady Bunch'';<ref name=\"Source1\" /> it includes a picture of a two-year-old McCormick dressed as a [[cowgirl]].<ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> The cover, however, bore a sticker saying \"Marcia Marcia Marcia\", which McCormick said was done by a public relations company and described its inclusion as \"a ''big'' mistake\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" />\n\nMcCormick told ''Billboard'' she felt \"optimistic\" that [[country radio]] would accept her music.<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\" /> During a 1995 interview, she said people, particularly [[DJ]]s, enjoyed the album and her voice; ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''{{'s}} Gary McKechnie wrote that it \"seem[ed] to be popular with country music fans\".<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> The song \"When You Get a Little Lonely\" was the [[lead single]] and promoted through a [[music video]].<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\" /> The video was shown on the 1995 [[television special]] ''Brady Bunch Home Movies''.<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\" /><ref name=\"NewspaperStorm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178196364/|url-access=subscription|title=''The Brady Bunch'' and ''Laverne & Shirley'' get nostalgia treatment|last=Storm|first=Jonathan|date=August 16, 1995|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> \"Tell Mama\" was released in September 1995 as the second single.<ref name=\"NewspaperFried\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/275713505/|url-access=subscription|title=National Catfish Month survey says consumers like it fried|last=|first=|date=August 16, 1995|work=[[Clarksdale Press Register]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was made available as a [[Digital download (music)|digital download]] on [[Apple Music]], but it was later removed from the platform.<ref name=\"DigitalDownload1\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely/260546168|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|website=[[Apple Music]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615233727/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely/260546168|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Record label Building re-released the album as an exclusive for [[Circuit City]] in 2008.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> It is McCormick's only album as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Biopgraphy1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/maureen-mccormick-21273345|title=Maureen McCormick Biography|date=August 31, 2016|work=Biography.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323140142/https://www.biography.com/people/maureen-mccormick-21273345|archivedate=March 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1994 ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' report, McCormick planned to promote ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' with a tour.<ref name=\"NewspaperSunTimes2\" /> She held album signings in 1995 at a Hollywood [[Virgin Megastores|Virgin Megastore]], the [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] [[record store]] Peaches Music & Video, and a [[Henrietta, New York|Henrietta]] [[Media Play]].<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /><ref name=\"HighBeam2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25001230.html|url-access=subscription|title=Hot Tips Y'All Should Hear That Brady Gal Sing|date=April 24, 1995|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25001230.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"Orlando2\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-04-17/news/9504170063_1_marsha-brady-brady-bunch-peaches-music|title=Who: Maureen McCormick, also known as Marsha Brady from...|date=May 17, 1995|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016150206/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-04-17/news/9504170063_1_marsha-brady-brady-bunch-peaches-music|archivedate=October 16, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of the Henrietta event, Media Play held a \"''Brady Bunch'' look-alike contest\".<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /> McCormick promoted the album by performing at [[Lake Compounce]], an amusement park in Bristol and Southington, Connecticut, on July 2, 1995.<ref name=\"NewspaperPerformances\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/176664069/|url-access=subscription|title=Marsha! Marsha! Marsha!|last=|first=|date=June 29, 1995|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> On October 21, 1995, she performed during an [[Indianapolis Ice]] game against the [[Detroit Vipers]]. She also signed autographs during the game's intermission as part of a \"Brady Bunch Night\".<ref name=\"Newspaper6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/313324188/|url-access=subscription|title='Bunch' of fun is expected when 'Marcia' joins the Ice|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1995|work=[[Indianapolis News]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> The following year, she sang at the Palmdale Playhouse in [[Palmdale, California]].<ref name=\"HighBeam3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25037832.html|url-access=subscription|title=Palmdale Playhouse Opens '96 with Varied Fare|last=Thacker|first=Karen|date=January 8, 1996|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211423/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25037832.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In August 2001, McCormick appeared alongside her ''The Brady Bunch'' co-stars on the game show [[The Weakest Link (U.S. game show)|''The Weakest Link'']]. On his official website, [[Barry Williams (actor)|Barry Williams]], who played [[Greg Brady (Brady Bunch)|Greg Brady]], held a competition in which viewers could win prizes, one of which was a copy of ''When You Get a Little Lonely'', for guessing the winner of ''The Weakest Link'' correctly.<ref name=\"Newspaper7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/279195610/|url-access=subscription|title='Brady Bunch' cast reunites to compete on NBC's 'Weakest Link'|last=|first=|date=August 25, 2001|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|1.5|5}}<ref name=\"Source1\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|1|4}}<ref name=\"Newspaper5\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = F<ref name=\"Source5\" />\n| rev4 = ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''\n| rev4score = D\u2212<ref name=\"Time\" />\n}}\n''When You Get a Little Lonely'' received mainly negative reviews from critics. Some commentators recommended it for fans of ''The Brady Bunch''.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> Pemberton Roach described McCormick as a \"competent singer\" with enthusiasm but said her [[upper register]] was \"a little screechy at times\". Roach cited \"Cloud of Dust\" as a highlight but was less positive about the album as a whole and said it \"sounds like a well-produced L.A. songwriter demo\".<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Despite praising the song selection, ''[[Hartford Courant]]''{{'s}} Anita M. Seline criticized McCormick's voice, specifically on her \"tepid\" version of \"Oh Boy!\".<ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> A ''People'' writer suggested McCormick record pop music or covers of 1970s [[Top 40]] songs because \"kitschy stuff, after all, has a remarkable shelf life\". The reviewer said she \"doesn't bring much conviction to the material\" but her voice has a \"sweet, rather pure timbre&nbsp;... It's a very Brady sort of voice.\"<ref name=\"Source6\" /> Kathleen Adams and Lina Lofaro, writing for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' criticized McCormick's voice and said she \"shows scant vocal or emotional range and her backup musicians follow suit\".<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite journal|date=May 8, 1995|title=It didn't stop with William Shatner|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|volume=145|issue=19|pages=40|last1=Adams|first1=Kathleen|last2=Lofaro|first2=Lina|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators were critical of McCormick's decision to record country music. Alanna Nash panned ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"the most manufactured of country pop\" and criticized McCormick for singing with \"the overwrought exuberance of a high school variety show contestant\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''{{'s}} Miriam Longino wrote that she \"can carry a tune\" and that the album has the \"slickest arrangements and studio musicians\", but she largely dismissed it as \"a contrived attempt to cash in on country's popularity\". Longino said McCormick's interpretation of country music was inauthentic, writing, \"A pair of [[Tony Lama Boots|Tony Lama boots]] cannot transform this California actress into [[Patsy Cline]]\".<ref name=\"Newspaper5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/403240472/|url-access=subscription|title=''When You Get A Little Lonely''|last=Longino|first=Miriam|date=April 29, 1995|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A ''[[St. Cloud Times]]'' reviewer criticized her for \"tr[ying] her hand at country and go[ing] nowhere\".<ref name=\"Newspaper4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/225993301/|url-access=subscription|title=Country music's surge slows down in 1995|last=|first=|date=December 28, 1995|work=[[St. Cloud Times]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A ''Time'' contributor dismissed ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"new country curbed and gutted\".<ref name=\"Time\" /> In a 2010 ''[[Newsday]]'' article, Daniel Bubbeo wrote, \"it's doubtful [McCormick] caused [[Reba McEntire]] to have any sleepless nights\".<ref name=\"Newsday\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Maureen McCormick Maui crop.PNG|thumb|McCormick at a 2009 book signing|alt=A 2009 photograph of Maureen McCormick.]]\n\nIn a 2008 interview, McCormick said she was disappointed by the recording process for ''When You Get a Little Lonely'': \"I kinda felt like it wasn't done the right way. There are certain rules in Nashville, and my album didn't really follow them.\" She wished the process had been \"more organic\" and that she could have written at least one of the songs.<ref name=\"EW1\" />\n\nAccording to a 2015 AXS article, McCormick has \"long been associated with country music\", including her portrayal of [[Barbara Mandrell]] in the 1997 [[television film]] ''Get to the Heart: The Barbara Mandrell Story''.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> She [[Lip sync|lip-synced]] to Mandrell's music,<ref name=\"NewspaperPalm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/133287603/|url-access=subscription|title=Stretching It: From Marcia Brady to Barbara Mandrell|last=Thompson|first=Kevin D.|date=September 26, 1997|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> saying; \"Really, in a piece like this, you're playing that person. I would never be able to sound like her.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperKoko\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/2774745/|url-access=subscription|title=Barbara, Barbara, Barbara|last=Waldon|first=David Brian|date=September 15, 1997|work=[[Kokomo Tribune]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Also in 1997, McCormick was an opening act for [[Clint Black]] and [[Faith Hill]], and performed with [[Hal Ketchum]] and the [[Confederate Railroad]].<ref name=\"NewspaperPalm\" /><ref name=\"NewspaperDailyNews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/477521652/|url-access=subscription|title=There's a Song in Their Arts|last=Schulman|first=Sandra|date=August 31, 1997|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nMcCormick appeared in the music video for [[Brad Paisley]]'s 2007 song \"[[Online (song)|Online]]\".<ref name=\"Source4\" /> The following year, she competed on the first season of the reality television show [[Gone Country (TV series)|''Gone Country'']];<ref name=\"Source4\" /> as the prize, [[John Rich]] would produce the winner's song, and it would be sent to radio.<ref name=\"EW1\" /> McCormick said it was a \"lifelong dream to have a song on the radio\".<ref name=\"Source4\" /> In March 2008, [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]] was announced as the winner of the season.<ref name=\"CMT1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmtpress.com/press-release/julio-iglesias-jr-tapped-by-host-john-rich-as-cmts-hit-series-gone-country-winner/|title=Julio Iglesias, Jr Tapped by Host John Rich as CMT's Hit Series ''Gone Country'' Winner|date=March 10, 2008|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Access Hollywood]]''{{'s}} executive producer Rob Silverstein hired McCormick as a red-carpet reporter for the [[2008 CMT Music Awards]] after seeing her on ''Gone Country''.<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits are taken from the booklet of ''When You Get a Little Lonely''. Barry Coffing produced all of the songs.<ref name=\"Source0\" />\n\n{{Tracklist\n| total_length    = 34:41\n| title1 = When You Get a Little Lonely\n| writer1 = [[Nicolette Larson]], Wendy Waldman, [[Josh Leo]]\n| length1 = 4:03\n| title2 = I'd Have to Call It Love\n| writer2 = [[Robert Ellis Orrall]]\n| length2 = 3:17\n| title3 = Tell Mama\n| writer3 = Barry Coffing\n| length3 = 3:03\n| title4 = Some Somebody\n| writer4 = [[Troy Seals]], [[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]], Rhonda Gunn\n| length4 = 3:28\n| title5 = We Must Have Done Something Right\n| note5 = featuring [[Wayland Patton]]\n| writer5 = Marc Beeson, [[Liz Hengber]]\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = [[Cloud of Dust]]\n| writer6 = [[Judy Rodman]], Tom Damphier\n| length6 = 3:15\n| title7 = Go West\n| writer7 = [[Gretchen Peters]]\n| length7 = 2:53\n| title8 = [[Oh, Boy! (The Crickets song)|Oh, Boy!]]\n| writer8 = [[Norman Petty]], Bill Tilghman, Sonny West\n| length8 = 3:03\n| title9 = Might as Well Be Me\n| writer9 = [[Pam Tillis]], [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]\n| length9 = 2:52\n| title10 = I Do But I Don't\n| writer10 = [[Foster & Lloyd|Bill Lloyd]], Mark Irwin\n| length10 = 2:37\n| title11 = I Can't Say\n| writer11 = George Teren, Bob Regan\n| length11 = 2:41\n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nThe following credits were adapted from the booklet of ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' and AllMusic:<ref name=\"Source0\" /><ref name=\"Source2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/credits|title=Credits|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/credits|archivedate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* Richard Abramson&nbsp;\u2013 stylist\n* Osama Afifi&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* [[Barry Beckett]]&nbsp;\u2013 organ (Hammond)\n* Marc Beeson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Chris Bellman&nbsp;\u2013 mixing\n* Mike Botts&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* Carter Bradley&nb