ill<ref name=\"Coffing1\" /><ref name=\"Source3\" />\n|-\n| 1998\n| CD\n| Building<ref name=\"Source3\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Peppiatt|first1=Francesca|title=Country Music's Most Wanted: The Top 10 Book of Cheatin' Hearts, Honky-Tonk Tragedies, and Music City Oddities|year=2004|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc|location=Dulles|pages=|isbn=1-57488-593-6|ref=Peppiatt2004}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs release|type=album|5166370|name=When You Get a Little Lonely}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:1995 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Maureen McCormick albums]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1004:b14e:5d8a:606d:4e82:b02d:cfaf", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Alll)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/When_You_Get_a_Little_Lonely"}
{"title_page": "Howden Reservoir", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox lake\n | name = Howden Reservoir\n | image = Howden Dam.jpg\n | caption = Howden Dam from Abbey Bank (Dec 2010)\n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location =  [[Derbyshire]] and [[South Yorkshire]]\n | coords = {{coord|53|26|N|1|45|W|region:GB_type:waterbody_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n | lake_type = [[reservoir]]\n | inflow = [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]], [[River Westend]], [[Howden Clough]] and [[Linch Clough]]\n | outflow = [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]]\n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United Kingdom\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = \n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n\nThe '''Howden Reservoir''' is a Y-shaped [[reservoir (water)|reservoir]], top one of the three in the [[Upper Derwent Valley]], England. The western half of the reservoir lies in [[Derbyshire]], whereas the eastern half is in [[Sheffield]], South Yorkshire. The county border runs through the middle of the reservoir, following the original path of the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]]. The longest arm is around 1.25 miles (2&nbsp;km) in length. The reservoir is bounded at the southern end by Howden Dam; below this, the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]] flows immediately into [[Derwent Reservoir, Derbyshire|Derwent Reservoir]] and subsequently the [[Ladybower Reservoir]].   Other tributaries include the [[River Westend]], [[Howden Clough]] and [[Linch Clough]].\n\nWork commenced on the dams construction on 16 July 1901 and completed in July 1912.  The chief engineer was <nowiki>Mr Edward Sandeman</nowiki>. He was also in charge of building nearby Derwent dam and he was awarded the [[Telford Medal]] in 1918 for his work \u2018Derwent Valley Waterworks\u2019. The works involved constructing a temporary village at [[Birchinlee]], or \"Tin Town\", for the workers, a temporary railway line from the main line at [[Bamford]], construction of a link aqueduct to the Derwent Dam. The dam is of solid masonry construction, and {{convert|117|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=mid|tall}}, {{convert|1080|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=mid|long}}, and impounds {{convert|1,900,000|impgal|kl}} of water, from a catchment area of {{convert|5155|acre|km2}}. The workers who died during the construction of the dam were buried in [[Bamford Church]].\n\nTo the east of the reservoir stands Featherbed Moss, one of the highest tops in the area at 545 m, and one of several tops of that name in the area. This is not to be confused with the more well-known [[Featherbed Moss]] on the Pennine Way between Kinder Scout and Bleaklow.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:howdenoverflow.JPG|Reservoir and Dam (July 2007)\nFile:Howden dam(large).jpg|Base of Howden Dam, from Derwent Reservoir\n</gallery>\n\n{{commonscat|Howden Reservoir}}\n{{Derbyshire Places of interest}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Dams completed in 1912]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Derwent (Derbyshire) catchment|RHowden]]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox lake\n | name = Howden Reservoir\n | image = Howden Dam.jpg\n | caption = Howden Dam from Abbey Bank (Dec 2010)\n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location =  [[Derbyshire]] and [[South Yorkshire]]\n | coords = {{coord|53|26|N|1|45|W|region:GB_type:waterbody_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n | lake_type = [[reservoir]]\n | inflow = [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]], [[River Westend]], [[Howden Clough]] and [[Linch Clough]]\n | outflow = [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]]\n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United Kingdom\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = \n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n\nThe '''Howden Reservoir''' is a Y-shaped [[reservoir (water)|reservoir]], top one of the three in the [[Upper Derwent Valley]], England. The western half of the reservoir lies in [[Derbyshire]], whereas the eastern half is in [[Sheffield]], South Yorkshire. The county border runs through the middle of the reservoir, following the original path of the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]]. The longest arm is around 1.25 miles (2&nbsp;km) in length. The reservoir is bounded at the southern end by Howden Dam; below this, the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]] flows immediately into [[Derwent Reservoir, Derbyshire|Derwent Reservoir]] and subsequently the [[Ladybower Reservoir]].   Other tributaries include the [[River Westend]], [[Howden Clough]] and [[Linch Clough]].\n\nWork commenced on the dams construction on 16 July 1901 and completed in July 1912.  The chief engineer was <nowiki>Mr Edward Sandeman</nowiki>. He was also in charge of building nearby Derwent dam and he was awarded the [[Telford Medal]] in 1918. The works involved constructing a temporary village at [[Birchinlee]], or \"Tin Town\", for the workers, a temporary railway line from the main line at [[Bamford]], construction of a link aqueduct to the Derwent Dam. The dam is of solid masonry construction, and {{convert|117|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=mid|tall}}, {{convert|1080|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=mid|long}}, and impounds {{convert|1,900,000|impgal|kl}} of water, from a catchment area of {{convert|5155|acre|km2}}. The workers who died during the construction of the dam were buried in [[Bamford Church]].\n\nTo the east of the reservoir stands Featherbed Moss, one of the highest tops in the area at 545 m, and one of several tops of that name in the area. This is not to be confused with the more well-known [[Featherbed Moss]] on the Pennine Way between Kinder Scout and Bleaklow.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:howdenoverflow.JPG|Reservoir and Dam (July 2007)\nFile:Howden dam(large).jpg|Base of Howden Dam, from Derwent Reservoir\n</gallery>\n\n{{commonscat|Howden Reservoir}}\n{{Derbyshire Places of interest}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Dams completed in 1912]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Derwent (Derbyshire) catchment|RHowden]]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MichaelDominicSomervell", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added more details", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howden_Reservoir"}
{"title_page": "Hay Dale", "text_new": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Hay Dale|map_alt=|photo=Hay Dale on Limestone Way.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=Hay Dale on the Limestone Way|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2902|-1.8207|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|elevation_ref=|direction=North-South|length={{Convert|0.75|mi|0}}|width={{Convert|120|m|0}}|area=|depth={{Convert|30|m|0}}|type=|elevation_m=|boundaries=|topo=|towns=|traversed=|watercourses=|footnotes=|embed=}}\n[[File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|thumb|Northern End of Hay Dale]]\n'''Hay Dale''' is a short dry valley near [[Buxton]], [[Derbyshire]], in the [[Peak District]] of England. The foot of the valley leads into Peter Dale to the south and on into [[Monk's Dale]].<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nHay Dale is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]]. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] ([[Lathkill Dale]], [[Cressbrook Dale]], Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale]]). The [[Carboniferous Limestone|Carboniferous limestone]] rocks of the reserve were formed 350 million years ago from the shells and sediments of a tropical sea. The landscape was then scuplted by the ice sheets from the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] 20,000 years ago. The reserve contains ash woodland, limestone grassland and many wildflowers including [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]], [[Primula veris|cowslip]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock rose]] and [[Thymelaeaceae|thyme]]. Butterfies are abundant and include the [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]].<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Limestone Way]] long-distance footpath runs along the length of the gentle valley floor. The [[Pennine Bridleway]] crosses the northern end of the dale. Where the Limestone Way crosses the A623 road (about 1kn north of Hay Dale), the route of the old [[Batham Gate]] [[Roman roads|Roman road]] runs east-west.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nAccess into Haydale from the South can be made from the village of Wormhill along the Pennine Bridleway and through Peter Dale. From the North there is a footpath from the village on Peak Forest (on the A623 road) through Dam Dale.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Hay Dale|map_alt=|photo=Hay Dale on Limestone Way.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=Hay Dale on the Limestone Way|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2902|-1.8207|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|elevation_ref=|direction=North-South|length={{Convert|0.75|mi|0}}|width={{Convert|120|m|0}}|area=|depth={{Convert|30|m|0}}|type=|elevation_m=|boundaries=|topo=|towns=|traversed=|watercourses=|footnotes=|embed=}}\n[[File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|thumb|Northern End of Hay Dale]]\n'''Hay Dale''' is a short dry valley near [[Buxton]], [[Derbyshire]], in the [[Peak District]] of England. The foot of the valley leads into Peter Dale to the south and on into [[Monk's Dale]].<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nHay Dale is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]]. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] ([[Lathkill Dale]], [[Cressbrook Dale]], Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale]]). The [[Carboniferous Limestone|Carboniferous limestone]] rocks of the reserve were formed 350 million years ago from the shells and sediments of a tropical sea. The landscape was then scuplted by the ice sheets from the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] 20,000 years ago. The reserve contains ash woodland, limestone grassland and many wildflowers including [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]], [[Primula veris|cowslip]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock rose]] and [[Thymelaeaceae|thyme]]. Butterfies are abundant and include the [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]].<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Limestone Way]] long-distance footpath runs along the length of the gentle valley floor. The [[Pennine Bridleway]] crosses the northern end of the dale. Where the Limestone Way crosses the A623 road (about 1kn north of Hay Dale), the route of the old [[Batham Gate]] [[Roman roads|Roman road]] runs east-west.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nAccess into Haydale from the South can be made from the village of Wormhill along the Pennine Bridleway and through Peter Dale. From the North there is a footpath from the village on Peak Forest (on the A623 road) through Dam Dale.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed duplicate section heading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hay_Dale"}
